INSERT INTO `content_larges` VALUES (1,2,'Amaranth','*Amaranthus spp.*','Amaranthaceae','','The leaves are good in the summer (usually best early on), and the seeds are ripe in the fall, the greatest harvest being in mid-fall.<br />','Amaranth grows in fields, disturbed habitats, roadsides, and cultivated areas throughout North America.<br />','Various species grow throughout the continental US.<br />','Look for large, dense, coarse clusters of tiny green flower masses in mid- to late summer, and similar clusters of seeds in the fall.<br />','This group of nearly 40 weedy looking, leafy plants, 2 to 8 feet tall, bears distinct, large, dense, upright spikes of tiny seeds. There\'s no strong, distinct odor.<br /><br />Coarse, oval to lance-shaped, long-stalked, alternate, toothless leaves grow from 1 to 2 inches long.<br /><br />Thousands of tiny, green, inconspicuous flowers, surrounded by hair-like bracts (small modified leaves), create conspicuous, dense masses in the summer. Then thousands of tiny, round, black seeds, also in dense clusters, and surrounded by the papery bracts, cram into the same locations in autumn. ','1. Leaves:<br /><br />Simply strip off the leaves from young plants. A few pieces of tender leaf stalks and stems are alright to include.<br /><br />2. Seeds:<br /><br />Look for amaranth where it\'s very abundant. Clip off large numbers of seed clusters with kitchen scissors, pruning shears, or a pocket knife. Put them in paper supermarket shopping bags and let them dry out a few weeks (you can store them indefinitely that way). Rub the dry seed heads (this works with fresh seed heads too, but it\'s much less efficient) over a bowl to remove the seeds. Transfer to a tray or cookie sheet and blow a fan across the tray over the sink, or outdoors, to get rid of the chaff.  (Note: The author and app developer disavow all responsibility for any and all housecleaning bills incurred if the chaff makes a mess in your kitchen.)<br /><br />Use the seeds immediately, or store indefinitely in tightly closed jars.<br /><br />','1. Leaves:<br /><br />The leaves are unpleasantly bitter raw. Serve them to a raw food enthusiast you don\'t like. But they\'re excellent cooked. Add them to soups, stews, sauces (especially tomato sauce), or vegetable dishes. They\'re also great saut?©ed or steamed, and strong-tasting enough that you can stir in your favorite spices or sauce in the end, or just serve with salt and pepper, and a dash of olive or sesame oil. They cook in about 10 minutes.<br /><br />2. Seeds:<br /><br />Although not technically a grain, you can cook the nutty flavored seeds as you would a grain: Boil them in water to cover for about 15 minutes, or until the water is absorbed and the seeds are soft, like rice. You may use soy-, nut-, or oat milk instead of water, plus fresh or dried fruit, sweet herbs (i.e., mint, cinnamon, ginger), and a sweetener, to make a sweet hot cereal. To make them more nutty tasting, toast the seeds in a pan over medium until they pop, stirring very often, before adding the liquid.<br /><br />Amaranth seeds are also an excellent included in grain dishes, upping the flavor and nutrition, i.e., as part of a rice pilaf or stuffing. Try using 4 parts oats and 1 part toasted amaranth in your favorite oatmeal recipe, cooked with raisins and fresh fruit.',NULL,'','Because this is a large group of species, a number of other plants resemble them enough to cause confusion when they\'re all young, so you should wait until you see the distinctive large, dense seed spikes before harvesting the first time. You can always return for the leaves the following year, much easier to do if you\'re still alive!<br /><br />Lamb\'s-quarters, also edible, is probably the most similar-looking plant, but it\'s leaves are diamond-shaped and toothed, and its seed spikes are comparatively sparse. Both plants are sometimes called pigweed, a confusing name better avoided!','1. Leaves:<br /><br />The leaves are unpleasantly bitter raw. Serve them to a raw food enthusiast you don\'t like. But they\'re excellent cooked. Add them to soups, stews, sauces (especially tomato sauce), or vegetable dishes. They\'re also great sautéed or steamed, and strong-tasting enough that you can stir in your favorite spices or sauce in the end, or just serve with salt and pepper, and a dash of olive or sesame oil. They cook in about 10 minutes.<br /><br />2. Seeds:<br /><br />Although not technically a grain, you can cook the nutty flavored seeds as you would a grain: Boil them in water to cover for about 15 minutes, or until the water is absorbed and the seeds are soft, like rice. You may use soy-, nut-, or oat milk instead of water, plus fresh or dried fruit, sweet herbs (i.e., mint, cinnamon, ginger), and a sweetener, to make a sweet hot cereal. To make them more nutty tasting, toast the seeds in a pan over medium until they pop, stirring very often, before adding the liquid.<br /><br />Amaranth seeds are also an excellent included in grain dishes, upping the flavor and nutrition, i.e., as part of a rice pilaf or stuffing. Try using 4 parts oats and 1 part toasted amaranth in your favorite oatmeal recipe, cooked with raisins and fresh fruit.<br />','The leaves are astringent. An infusion has been used as a gargle for hoarseness, as well as for diarrhea, excessive menstruation, and intestinal bleeding.','Don\'t harvest Amaranth if Cortez is around. He made amaranth illegal when he conquered the Aztec Indians, objecting to its use in human sacrifice (while in his native Spain, the Inquisition was burning people at the stake for religious crimes such as being Jewish), and incidentally weakening them through starvation, so he could steal their gold. The punishment for possession of this controlled substance was death!','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2,4,'asd','','','','dsd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,'D',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(3,9,'Chicory','*Cichorium intybus*','Family *Asteraceae  (Compositae),* the astor or composite family','','Leaves: Early spring and late fall, plus winter if mild<br />Flowers: Late spring to early fall<br />Taproot (for making coffee): Early spring to late fall (and winter in mild climates)','Chicory needs full sunlight and well-drained soil, and thrives in disturbed habitats, roadsides, fields, and parks.','Chicory grows throughout most of the continental US and Canada.','In cold-weather seasons, look for basal rosettes of jagged, dandelion-like leaves with teeth pointing outward, and reddish midribs. In the summer, look for nearly leafless stalks around 4 feet tall with showy, sky-blue composite flowers consisting of fringed ray flowers and no disk flowers.','This is a very common, widespread perennial, similar to the related dandelion when young, with basal leaves 3 to 10 inches long,  tastes like dandelions and commercial chicory (which is also a different species). The sky-blue composite flowers make it easy to spot when it dominates roadsides in the summer. The whole plant exudes a white, milky latex when cut.<br /><br />Chicory forms a basal rosette very early in the spring. The basal leaves begin lance-shaped, with small teeth, but the teeth soon become quite large, like dandelion\'s, although chicory\'s leaves\' teeth often point outward, not always toward the leaf\'s base, like dandelions\'. Chicory\'s leaf\'s midrib has some hair (dandelions\' don\'t), and usually some red color.<br /><br />A zigzag flower stalk 1.5 to 4 feet tall (sometimes taller) with tiny, barely noticeable, alternate, lance-shaped, stalkless, toothed leaves comes up in the summer (its woody skeleton persists through winter), bearing 15 to 20 showy, blue, stalked, composite flower heads with fringed ray flowers, but no disk flowers, and many stamens ending in the letter \"Y.\" The tiny, inconspicuous seeds that follow blow away in the wind.<br /><br />Chicory usually grows in dense stands.<br /><br />A deep, stiff, beige, perennial taproot usually grows much longer than a carrot\'s.','Collect the leaves of the smallest basal rosettes before the teeth get large and the leaves become too bitter to be palatable, in very early spring, or if new growth appears in late fall. Pass a sharp knife under the rosette to sever it from the taproot—much more efficient that picking off the leaves a few at a time.<br /><br />You can also dig up the root for making coffee any time of year with a shovel—much easier than using a trowel. Do so after it\'s rained, when the soil is more yielding, and choose a location that isn\'t rocky.','The leaves have a robust, dandelion-lettuce flavor, with a hint of bitterness that must be managed wisely. Use the leaves like dandelion leaves. Add the young leaves sparingly to salads or sandwiches. Too many may create too much bitterness.<br /><br />Or sauté them in olive (or other) oil with herbs and spices, then add a sauce consistent with a culinary tradition that uses the same spices (i.e., Mexican spices + salsa) and simmer. Leaves shrink when you sauté them, concentrating the bitterness, but this method nullifies the phenomenon. Adding the sautéed greens to soups or stews, i.e., one containing beans or noodles, also works well.<br /><br />The roots are usually too tough and woody to eat (although you can cook them, after which they\'ll taste like cooked wood!), but you can chop them, then roast them at 350 degrees for an hour, stirring occasionally, chop further to the size of coffee in a blender or coffee- or spice grinder, and brew into a well-known coffee substitute.','• Basal rosette of deeply toothed leaves with some of the teeth pointing outward<br />• White, milky sap wherever the plant is broken<br />• Often reddish midrib in the basal leaves<br />• Some fine hairs on the midrib<br />• Woody remnants of a flower stalk connected to many of the rosettes in early spring and fall<br />• Deep, stiff taproot<br />• Blue composite flowers with fringe-tipped rays mostly in the summer<br />• Zigzag, nearly bare flower stalk, up to 4 feet tall, with very small, alternate, toothed, lance-shaped leaves',NULL,'1. When they\'re very young, dandelion rosettes, also edible, resemble chicory rosettes, but dandelions\' basal leaves\' teeth always point to the leaf\'s base. Some of chicory\'s leaves\' teeth point outward. Chicory\'s basal leaves\' midribs are often tinged reddish, with some fine hairs, qualities dandelions lack. Many chicory rosettes have remnants of the previous year\'s woody flower stalks, which dandelions lack. When they flower, dandelions have familiar yellow flowers, while chicory grows a tall flower stalk with many blue flowers.<br />2. Young wild lettuce rosettes resemble chicory rosettes, but wild lettuce has fibrous roots, never a taproot, and it\'s midrib is triangular in cross-section. Later on, its flowers are yellow, like dandelions\'.<br />3. Commercial chicory, which doesn\'t grow wild in the US, is actually a different species, *Cichorium endivia,* also called curly endive.','The leaves are an excellent source of calcium, and they also provide some potassium, phosphorus, copper, zinc, magnesium, and vitamins A, K, C, E, plus some B-complex vitamins.','Like its relative, the dandelion, which has superseded it in modern herbal practice, a decoction of the root has been used for various liver problems, and to aid digestion.','','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(4,15,'Burdock','*Arctium minus,* common burdock; and *A. lappa,* greater burdock','Family: *Asteraceae,* Aster family','','Taproot of 1st year plant: Spring, summer, and fall<br />Taproot of 2nd year plant: Spring, before the flower stalk appears<br />Flower stalk: mid-spring<br />Leave stalks of greater burdock: spring, summer, and fall','Burdock grows in the sun or partial shade, in disturbed soil, backyards, untended gardens, empty lots, overgrown fields, empty lots, meadows, edge habitats, and urban parks.','Burdock grows across most of North America and much of Canada, except in the deep south.','Look for the basal rosettes of large, coarse, wedge-shaped leaves, whitish underneath, the tall flower stalks bearing purple, shaving brush-shaped flowers, and the brown, prickly burrs.','This is a delicious root vegetable, prized in east Asia, with the bonus of an edible immature flower stalk, which is prized in Italy.<br /><br />Leaves: This coarse-looking biennial has huge, wedge-shaped leaves up to 2 feet long and 1 foot broad, forming a basal rosette the first year, and at the beginning of the second year. Unlike similar plants, the leaves are whitish and finely wooly underneath.<br /><br />Leaf stalks: The purplish-green leaf stalks can grow up to 1.5 feet long and .75 inch thick. Common burdock\'s leaf stalks are hollow, not furrowed. Greater burdock\'s leaf stalks are solid, with a groove along the upper surface.<br /><br />Taproot: The taproot, whitish after being scrubbed, consists of an outer rind and inner core, and can grow up to 4 feet long and 3 inches wide. It smells like potatoes and dirt. (After you scrub it, it smells like potatoes.)<br /><br />Flower stalk: The erect flower stalk, which arises from the center of the basal rosette in mid-spring of the second year, grows from 2 to 5 feet tall in common burdock and up to 9 feet tall in greater burdock.<br /><br />Flowers: Arising from green bases, the bristly, purple-pink, spherical, composite flowers, short-stemmed and 3/4 inch across in common burdock, long-stemmed and 1 to 1.5 inches across in greater burdock, resemble shaving brushes.<br /><br />Fruits: The ripe fruits, the inspiration for Velcro, consist of spherical burrs the size of the flowers, covered with tiny hooks. They stick to virtually anything they touch. Inside are many small, hard, curved, brown seeds.','Taproot: Burdock is a deep root that comes from Asia, and when you try to harvest it, you\'ll soon realize there\'s a hungry Asian person trying to pull it out from the opposite direction! There are 3 things you need to make this job relatively easy.<br />1. A shovel<br />2. A location where burdock is growing that\'s relatively free of rocks (not hard to do, since burdock is so common).<br />3. Moist soil, from a period where there\'s been plenty of rain, not a time when it hasn\'t rained for weeks, and the soil is rock hard.<br />Place the shovel an inch from the center of the rosette. Aim straight down, so you don\'t cut through the root. Grip the handle firmly with both hands. Repeatedly stomp on the shovel as hard as you can, to drive it all the way into the earth. Now, you can chance pushing upward with the shovel while gently pulling the leaves, and you may unearth the root, or most of the root, with no further effort. If it\'s unyielding, don\'t yank off the leaves, but remove the clod of soil with the shovel and repeat the process on the other side of the plant. When you\'re done, refill the hole with soil, so you\'ll create no environmental impact.<br />Flower Stalk: Cut the flower stalk with a pocket knife or pruning shears soon after it appears in mid-spring, while it\'s still very soft and flexible, long before the flowers appear.<br />Leaf Stalks: Cut them with a pocket knife any time, but only use greater burdock. There\'s not enough food in common burdock to make it worthwhile.','Taproot: The root tastes like a combination of potatoes and artichokes. Scrub the taproot with a metal scouring pad under running water to clean it. Slice diagonally, razor thin, or use the finest slicing blade of a food, so the root becomes tender more quickly. Do not discard the outer layer. It\'s just as good as the core. Digging up burdock takes some effort, so you\'re not going to want to throw out half your harvest for nothing!<br /><br />Burdock root is best simmered or steamed 15 to 20 minutes, or until tender, i.e., in soups, stews or casseroles. You can sauté it first if desired, but cooking it in liquid is also important to tenderize it. You can also bake it in a covered baking dish that includes liquid, so the hot steam tenderizes it.<br /><br />It\'s not poisonous raw, but it\'s probably hard to digest, and members of traditional cultures cooked it even in the days where going out to gather firewood could be dangerous.<br /><br />Flower stalk: Peel the fiber off the flower stalk (you may want to wear rubber gloves when you handle it, since it can stain your hands brown), slice, and pre-boil 1 minute to remove the bitterness. Cook it in any vegetable dish for 5 to 15 more minutes. It tastes like artichoke hearts.<br /><br />You can use greater burdock\'s leaf stalks the same way. Although there\'s way more food in the flower stalk, it\'s in season for only a short time.<br /><br />Leaves: The leaves are so bitter, if you squeeze one and touch your finger to your tongue, you\'ll wish you hadn\'t! Some people boil the very young leaves in multiple changes of water to get rid of the bitterness, but there are so many superior wild greens, you\'d make much better use of your time and effort learning them!','•Basal rosette of wedge-shaped, long-stalked, very large leaves (except when they\'re first emerging, in early spring) that are finely wooly and whitish underneath.<br />•Long taproot that\'s whitish when scrubbed, consisting of an outer rind and inner core.<br />•Flower stalk 2 to 9 feet tall with purple, shaving brush flowers giving way to ovate burrs bearing tiny hooks.','Cocklebur *(Xanthium spp.)* has burrs too, but they\'re arranged spirally, the rest of the plant doesn\'t look like burdock, you don\'t eat burdock when it has burrs, and I doubt anyone has ever been poisoned confusing the 2, but you should be aware of the possibility of confusion.','\"Dock\" means deduct or remove, and unrelated plants that people remove from their gardens, such as curly dock, a.k.a. yellow dock *(Rumex crispus)*, have the same confusing last name.<br />On the other hand, the unrelated bitter or broadleaf dock *(Rumex obtusifolia)* has large leaves that do resemble burdock\'s, and the plants sometimes grow side-by-side, but as a relative of yellow dock, bitter dock\'s hard, inedible taproot is bright yellow when scraped, and the leaves don\'t have burdock\'s white, wooly fuzz underneath. Although nonpoisonous, all parts of this plant usually taste so bad, eating them will make you wish you were dead!','Burdock root provides vitamins B6 and C, magnesium, phosphorus, potassium, manganese, and sodium. It\'s an excellent source of inulin, a polysaccharide that doesn\'t elicit an insulin response, and is beneficial to people with blood sugar problems.<br />','A decoction made by boiling the root has been used for centuries in Europe and Asia as a blood purifier (detoxifier in modern parlance), and for the skin, liver, and kidneys. A poultice made by mixing the chopped leaves with clay and water, and bandaged to bruises, clears the them in a few days. Burn care workers have reputedly had success applying the leaves topically to inhibit bacterial growth, speed healing time, and ease  the changing of dressings.','Don\'t eat the seeds, they may be poisonous (and they\'re too hard to eat anyway). And the burrs may actually be fatal—by the time you remove all the itchy fragments from your clothing, you could die of old age!','','','','',NULL,0,'1','',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(5,24,'Chickweed','*Stellaria media,* common chickweed; and *S. pubera,* star chickweed ','*Caryophyllaceae,* the pink family or carnation family','','Chickweed is in season all year, even growing in the winter any time it\'s above freezing, but it\'s at its best in early spring and late fall.<br />','Chickweed grows in lawns, meadows, gardens, and disturbed areas, in full sunlight and partial shade. In very cold weather, look for it along sun-heated walls with southern exposure, where it thrives in the milder microhabitat.','Various chickweed species grow throughout North America','Look for mats of slender-stemmed plants with opposite leaves and star-like flowers growing where there\'s at least some sun, especially during the colder times of the year when there\'s less greenery around.<br />','This is a common, delicious, healthful, widespread plant with a long season and wide range.<br />This small, sprawling annual\'s slender stem bears a distinctive row of fine white hairs, and tiny, smooth-edged, spade-shaped to oval, opposite leaves. Unlike some other ground-hugging plants, it never forms a basal rosette.<br />Common chickweed\'s leaves have short leaf stalks, while star chickweed has stalkless leaves.<br />Tiny, white flowers grow at the tips of the plants, with 5 petals so deeply split that they look like ten. Five green sepals surround the petals.<br />Tiny yellow-brown, oval-shaped seeds fall out of tiny ovate, stalked capsules before the plant dies.','Grab and bag the entire plant where it\'s plentiful, avoiding any with yellowed leaves or discolored stems, or clip with shears, a pocket knife, or scissors.','The whole plant, except the roots, is delicious! Collect it where it\'s abundant and thriving, while it\'s young and bright green, before it begins to go to seed, becomes light green, and gets stringy.<br /><br />A salad vegetable and potherb par excellence, always chop the entire plant, except the roots, into bite-sized pieces first. It gets its name because chickens love it, so you should eat it even if you\'re afraid to do so. In that case, you\'re chicken, and you\'ll love it!<br /><br />Raw it tastes like corn-on-the-cob, or like cornsilk. It\'s great in sandwiches, used like sprouts, especially in mid-Eastern recipes with hummus in pita bread. It\'s wonderful steamed, or added to soups, stews, and casseroles. You can also sauté it to. It cooks in about 5 minutes. Be careful not to overcook it.','•Mats of slender-stemmed plants growing close to the ground<br />•A thin line of tiny, white hairs along the stem<br />•Opposite leaves<br />•Tiny white flowers<br />•5 white petals each split into a \"V\"-shape that makes it look like 10 petals<br />•5 green sepals','Prostrate spurge *Euphorbia supina* and spotted spurge *E. maculata,* which grow close to the ground and have opposite leaves, look a little like chickweed, and they can grow side-by-side with chickweed. But spurge exudes a white, milky sap when cut. Chickweed doesn\'t. Spurge lacks chickweed\'s row of tiny white hairs growing along the stem. And spurge grows in rosettes, with many branches originating from a common point. Chickweed doesn\'t, although it does form mats.<br />Scarlet pimpernel is a small plant with opposite leaves that grows along the ground, but it lacks chickweed\'s row of fine hairs on the stem, and has an scarlet flower.','Other less common species of chickweed, also edible, grow throughout the US. Mouse-ear chickweed *(Cerastium vulgatum),* also with opposite leaves, is hairy all over. It\'s good cooked, but you won\'t enjoy it raw unless you like eating hairy food!<br /><br />Doorweed *(Polygonum aviculture)* looks a little like chickweed because it grows along the ground, sometimes along with chickweed, but its leaves are alternate, not opposite. Unlike chickweed, it grows in a basal rosette. And  there\'s no row of hair on the stems. Instead, the stems are punctuated by joints. The plant isn\'t poisonous, but, with the texture of string, it\'s not edible.','Chickweed is a nutritional powerhouse, providing vitamins C, A, D,  folic acid, riboflavin, niacin, and thiamine, as well as the minerals calcium, magnesium, potassium, manganese, zinc, iron, phosphorus, sodium, copper, silica.','Chickweed been applied topically to all kinds of skin sores and irritations for hundreds of years (you\'d think after all that time, the sores would finally heal!)<br /><br />Back in the day, while doctors were bleeding their patients, sometimes to death (that\'s how they finally got rid of George Washington\'s stubborn cold!), herbalists gave chickweed to convalescents after serious illnesses, to rebuild their strength, before opportunistic infections could cause a relapse. Turns out chickweed is loaded with more vitamins and minerals than a health food store, so it probably replaced the nutrients necessary for proper immune system function that were depleted during the illness.<br />','','','','','',NULL,0,'1','',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(6,32,'Common Plantain','*Plantago major* and *Plantago lancolata*','','','Spring, summer, and fall','This plant grows in sunny areas, partial shade, cultivated areas, lawns, meadows, parks, gardens, and fields, and on bare ground.','This European plants grows across the US and Canada, and virtually worldwide.','Look for basal rosettes of oval, ribbed leaves and pencil-shaped spikes of green flowers on lawns, and in sunny, grassy areas.','This common herb has minimal value as food, but it\'s among the most important medicinal plants you can find in the field.<br /><br />The oval leaves, which grow up to 6 inches long and 4 inches wide, form basal rosettes exclusively. Their ribbed appearance, created by parallel veins, makes them easy to recognize, as do the short, flattened, purple leaf stalks.<br /><br />The green, inconspicuous, wind-pollinated, pencil-shaped, leafless flower spike, with protruding white stamens, grows 6 to 8 inches tall, and blooms in the summer and fall. Inconspicuous, small, green, oblong fruits split open in late summer and fall to release tiny, black seeds.<br /><br />The roots are fibrous.','Pull off the leaves or flowers with your hand, or cut with a knife, and strip the immature, green fruits from the fruit stalk with your fingers.','This is one of the worst edible plants to use for food. Although you could eat the young leaves when they first appear in early spring, they\'re rather tough, and taste like wheat grass juice—a flavor few people love. The smaller leaves toward the center of the rosette are just as bad later on!<br /><br />I\'ve coated the leaves with olive oil, miso, and spices, and roasted them in a hot oven, as people sometimes do with kale, turning them often to prevent burning. They sometimes taste good this way, but other times there\'s an unpleasant, bitter aftertaste.<br /><br />The green, immature fruits taste like inferior peanuts—not worth the trouble. And the seeds inside the mature fruits, which you can use to thicken drinks, the way people use related psyllium seeds and flaxseeds, are so tiny, they\'re also not worth the effort.<br /><br />There\'s only 1 really good thing I can say about using common plantain as food. It\'s not quite as bad as its relative, long-leaf plantain!','•Basal rosettes of oval, ribbed leaves<br />•Short, flattened, purple leaf stalk<br />•Green, inconspicuous, pencil-shaped flowers<br />•Fibrous roots',NULL,'The closely related long-leaf plantain *(P. lanceolata)* has narrow, ribbed leaves, and a pineapple-shaped flower atop a sender, leafless flower stalk. You can use its leaves the same way as common plantain.<br /><br />The word \"plantain\" refers to the foot-like shape of this plant\'s leaf, but it\'s unrelated to the banana-like plantain. I don\'t know why they share a name.','Common plantain contains vitamins C and K, plus calcium, potassium, and sulfur, as well as trace minerals. The seeds are a good source of vitamin B1.','This is one of the best herbs for skin irritations, and it\'s been used as such since prehistoric times. Mash some leaves until they produce juice (some people chew them) and repeatedly apply this to a mosquito bite right after you\'ve been bitten. It will cure the bite in about 15 minutes. It lessens the effects of bee stings, it\'s good for scrapes, cooking burns, cuts, and poison ivy rash, with anti-inflammatory substances and chemicals that stop bleeding. It also contains allantoin, which promotes cell proliferation and healing.<br /><br />A tea of the mucilagenous seeds acts as a bulk laxative, good for constipation, and to relieve intestinal irritation.<br /><br />','','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(7,33,'Long-leaf Plantain','*Plantago lanceolata*','Family *Plantaginaceae,* plantain family','','Early spring to late fall, or all year where there are mild winters','This plant grows in sunny areas, partial shade, cultivated areas, lawns, meadows, parks, gardens, and fields, and on bare ground.','This European plants grows across the US and Canada, and virtually worldwide.','Look for basal rosettes of lance-shaped, ribbed leaves and a slender flower stalk topped with a small, inconspicuous, pineapple-shaped flower on lawns, and in sunny, grassy, and disturbed areas.','This common herb has minimal value as food, but it\'s an important medicinal species.<br /><br />The lance-shaped leaves, which grow up to 6 to 12 inches long, form basal rosettes exclusively. Their ribbed appearance, created by 3 or 5 parallel veins, makes them easy to recognize.<br /><br />A slender flower stalk growing less than 1 foot high supports a small, inconspicuous, cylindrical to pineapple-shaped brownish flower with protruding white stamens. It blooms from late spring to early fall.<br /><br />The roots are fibrous.','Pull off the leaves or flowers with your hand, or sever the rosette from the roots with a knife.','This is one of the worst edible plants to use for food. Although you could eat the young leaves when they first appear in early spring, they\'re rather tough, and taste like wheat grass juice—a flavor few people love. The smaller leaves toward the center of the rosette are just as good later on! Roasting the leaves, like I\'ve done with common plantain, doesn\'t work with this species, and the seeds are too small to use.','•Basal rosettes of lance-shaped, ribbed leaves<br />•Small, brownish, cylindrical to pineapple-shaped flower with protruding white stamens on a slender, leafless stalk<br />•Fibrous roots',NULL,'The closely related common plantain *(P. major)* has oval, ribbed leaves, and a green, pencil-shaped flower. You can use the leaves the same way.<br /><br />The word \"plantain\" refers to the foot-like shape of common plantain\'s leaf, but it\'s unrelated to the banana-like plantain. I don\'t know why they share a name.','Long-leaf plantain probably has the same nutrients as its relative, common plantain: vitamins C and K, plus calcium, potassium, and sulfur, as well as trace minerals.','This is an excellent plant for skin irritations. Mash some leaves until they produce juice (some people chew them) and repeatedly apply this to a mosquito bite right after you\'ve been bitten. It will cure the bite in about 15 minutes. It lessens the effects of bee stings, it\'s good for scrapes, cooking burns, cuts, and poison ivy rash, with anti-inflammatory substances and chemicals that stop bleeding. It also contains allantoin, which promotes cell proliferation and healing.<br />','','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(8,42,'Asiatic Dayflower','*Commelina communis*','','','Mid-spring through mid-fall','Asiatic dayflower grows in cultivated and disturbed areas, untended gardens, open places in woods, and on rocky soil.<br />','Asiatic dayflower grows throughout the Northeast. Its similar, larger, edible relative, Virginia dayflower *(C. virginica)* grows in the southeast, with the ranges overlapping partially. Other edible southeastern relatives grow westward to Texas or New Mexico.','Look for a medium-sized plant with 2 blue petals and one tiny transparent-white one, and grass-like, hairles, stalkless leaves with bases that wrap around the stem.','The nearly hairless plant (I can sympathize with its plight!) with distinct blue flowers usually grows only up to 1 foot tall, although under very favorable circumstances, it can reach a height of three feet. Very common, it\'s an excellent wild food.<br /><br />Flowers: This herbaceous (non-woody) annual bears two upper sky-blue petals about 1/2 inch long, and an smaller, inconspicuous, translucent-white lower petal. Each flower lives for but 1 day, but the large stands keep producing more flowers.<br /><br />Seeds: 2 short, elliptical sepals fuse to partially enclose 2 small, pale, yellow-green, slightly elongated pea-like seeds.<br /><br />Leaves: The simple, alternate, smooth-edged, pointed, grass-like leaves may be lance-shaped, or between oval and elliptical, and grow from 3 to 5 inches long. The stalkless leaves\' bases wrap around the stem to form a sheath. ','Strip off the leaves, flowers, tender portions of the stems, and seeds with your fingers. Avoid old, coarse, browning plants.','The leaves, flowers, young stems (while they\'re still tender), and seeds are fine in salads, and they\'re superb in soups or other vegetable dishes. They taste like string beans, and cook in about 10 minutes. Kids have fun picking out the seeds, which taste like green peas, and eating them separately, even though this is time-consuming.','•Medium-sized, virtually hairless plant under 1 foot tall<br />•2 upper blue petals 1/2 inch across<br />•Smaller whitish petal below<br />•Stalkless, alternate, grass-like leaves 3 to 5 inches long<br />•Leaf bases wrapping around the stem',NULL,'Virginia dayflower *(C. virginica),* also edible, is similar but larger. Other similar-looking close relatives in the South and Southwest are also edible. Spiderwort *(Tradescantia virginiana)* looks similar, but with 3 blue petals, and it grows much larger. It\'s edible before the leaves get too tough.<br /><br />Some non-poisonous grasses have similar leaves but totally different flowers, and they\'re way too hairy to tempt anyone to try to bite into them! ','No information is available.','An infusion of the plant has been used as an astringent for diarrhea, and as a gargle for sore throat and tonsilitis. Research has shown the plant to have anti-bacterial properties.','','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(9,48,'Common Mallow','*Malva neglecta*','Family: *Malveae,* mallow family','','Common Mallow is in season from early spring to late fall, also through the winter where winters are mild.','Common mallow grows in cultivated habitats such as gardens and parks, and along roadsides, in empty lots, and on disturbed soil, in sunny or partially shaded habitats.','Common mallow grows across most of the US and Canada.','Look for dense stands of creeping or upright plants with small, long-stalked, pleated, roundish, notched leaves, small, pinkish, notched, hibiscus-like flowers, and small, disk-shaped fruit that look like a wheel of cheese.','This readily available small plant, with long-stalked, roundish, pleated leaves, hibiscus-like flowers, and tiny fruits that resemble wheels of cheese, provides food most of the year.<br /><br />The crinkled, rounded to heart-shaped, toothed, slightly hairy basal leaves, and the similar alternate leaves on the main stem, grow from .75 to 2.5 inches across, with 5 to 7 shallow lobes. The leaf stalks can grow as long as 7 inches, and the leaf is notched where it connects to the leaf stalk.<br /><br />White to pale-pink or lavender, the 5-petaled, long-stalked flowers arise from the leaf axils.  Each flower, under .75 inches across, has 5 petals, with a bushy column of many stamens and 1 pistil in the center. Pink lines run the length of the petals, which are notched at the tips.<br /><br />.25 inch across, the flattened, rounded, stalked, segmented fruit is called a cheese because it looks like a tiny wheel of cheese.<br /><br />This perennial plant arises from a long, slender taproot. Its slender stems can creep along the ground or the plant can grow upright.','Hold down the stems with 1 hand and strip of leaves, flowers, and fruit with the other. Kids like to pick the fruits 1 at a time.','The chewy leaves, flowers, and fruits, which cook in about 10 minutes, impart a pleasant, mild flavor to salads, stews, grain dishes, and casseroles—especially good complimenting more flavorful ingredients. Like okra, this mucilaginous vegetable will thicken soups slightly.<br /><br />Kids love devouring the cheeses right of the plants as quickly as they can find them, and I enjoy the cheeses so much, I eat them at every opportunity, even though I\'m a vegan!<br /><br />People have tried boiling the roots to obtain a thickener, or cook and eat them, as with the much larger relative, the marshmallow, but they\'re way to small and fibrous to be worthwhile.','•Long-stalked, pleated, notched leaves .75 to 2 inches across<br />•Small, notched, lined, pinkish hibiscus-like flowers with bushy stamens<br />•Small, flattened, disk-shaped fruits .25 inch across resembling wheels of cheese<br />•Slender taproot',NULL,'Related species, such as the marsh mallow *(Althaea officinale),* which grows in swamps, are also edible, but much larger.','There\'s no information available.','Like its larger relative, the marsh mallow, tea made by boiling the roots is externally and internally soothing. It may be helpful for skin sores, stomach and duodenal ulcers, digestive tract irritations, urinary tract irritations or cystitis, as well as sore throats, irritated air passages, coughs, and bronchitis, and has been used as such for centuries, but it\'s never been subject to vigorous testing, so its effectiveness is still an open question.<br />','','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(10,54,'Curly Dock, Curled Dock, Yellow Dock','*Rumex crispus*','Family: *Polygonaceae,* the knotweed or smartweed family','','The basal leaves are in season in early spring, although there\'s sometimes new grow in late fall. The immature flower stalk and its leaves are in season in mid-spring, before the plant becomes too bitter to eat.','It grows in disturbed habitats and fields, and along roadsides and riverbanks.','It grows across the US and southern Canada.','Look for a large, coarse plant with long, broad basal leaves with curly margins; long clusters of tiny, green flowers or long clusters of tiny, reddish seeds growing on narrow, branching flower stalks with narrow, wavy, alternate leaves, and a yellow taproot.<br />Papery sheathes','This large, common spring green forms delicious basal rosettes early on, followed by tasty immature flower stalks.<br /><br />A basal rosette with hairless, toothless, stalked leaves, growing up to 2 feet long and up to nearly 2.5 inches wide, appears in early spring. The leaves\' very wavy margins make them distinct.<br /><br />In mid-spring, a flower stalk growing up to 3 feet tall appears, with narrow, alternate, very wavy leaves with shorter leaf stalks than the basal leaves. Many small, inconspicuous, green flowers, followed by numerous hard, reddish-brown seeds grow in dense clusters on the branched stems in summer and fall.<br /><br />A large, distinctively yellow, perennial, branching taproot grows underground (where else would you suppose it to be?), often supporting several stems.','Tear off the basal leaves with your hands or cut them off with a knife, scissors, or a shears. Cut off the immature flower stalks with a knife or shears. Dig up the root with a shovel (or use a trowel if you prefer to struggle.) ','In early spring, before the flower stalk appears, the basal leaves are excellent raw, in salads and sandwiches, and even better cooked. They cook surprisingly quickly, in about 2 minutes. The young leaf stalks are a little too tough to eat raw, but they cook in 2 to 3 minutes as well. The peeled immature flower stalks, which you collect in mid-spring, are good raw and excellent cooked as well.<br /><br />Curly dock as a wonderful lemony flavor raw, and the flavor intensifies when you cook it. Steam the leaves and stalks until just wilted (see the accompanying recipe), bake them in casseroles, or add them to soups or stews a couple of minutes before the cooking time ends.<br /><br />Caution: The very youngest curly dock leaves, when they\'ve just emerged from the ground and are no more than 2 or 3 inches long, can sometimes temporarily make your tongue numb if you eat them raw, perhaps from a concentration of oxalic acid crystals. Only use the very youngest leaves after you cook them, which eliminates the problem.<br /><br />Other writers have made a big deal about the dangers of curly dock\'s oxalic acid content, but this is completely wrong. There\'s no evidence of harm to any healthy individual eating large quantities of curly dock or spinach, which contains the same substance (although anyone with kidney disease warned about spinach by their doctor should use the same caution with curly dock), whereas thousands of people have been eating these plants for thousands of years and benefited from them. Just look at Popeye, who\'s been around since the 1920s!<br /><br />Although the seed clusters look like a very tempting source of food, the very tiny seeds inside are encased in so many layers of inedible tissues that anyone trying to harvest and use them winds up eating 99% chaff. Nevertheless, if you spend enough harvesting and preparing this trash, your brain may convince you that you\'re eating real food to justify all the hard work! ','•Basal rosette with large, long, narrow, hairless, toothless, very wavy edged leaves<br />•Large, yellow, branching taproot<br />•Branching, upright spikes up to 3 feet tall covered with many, tiny, inconspicuous green flowers, followed by hundreds of tiny, reddish-brown seeds','Caution: Never confuse curly dock with Moe dock or Larry dock (Nyuk! Nyuk! Nyuk!)','\"Dock\" means deduct or remove, and unrelated plants that people remove from their gardens, such as burdock *(Arctium spp.,)* have the same confusing last name. Burdock, with a whitish edible edible root and an edible immature flower stalk, has broad leaves without wavy margins that are finely whitish and wooly underneath.<br /><br />On the other hand, the related bitter or broadleaf dock *(Rumex obtusifolia)* has large leaves that do resemble curly dock\'s, and the plants sometimes grow side-by-side, but bitter dock has broader leaves without wavy margins. Although nonpoisonous, all parts of this plant usually taste so bad, they remind me of school lunch!','Curly dock is a great source of vitamin A and iron (herbalists prescribed it for anemia back in the day, and if the anemia was caused by iron deficiency, it worked), and a good source of thiamine (B1), riboflavin (B2), niacin, and vitamin C, as well as the minerals potassium, calcium, manganese, and phosphorus.','Curly dock has been used as a blood purifier or detoxifier, especially useful for skin conditions, glandular inflammation and swellings, for centuries. It contains rumicin, a liver decongestant that stimulates the liver to produce bile, which research has shown expels heavy metals from the body. A decoction has been used as a bitter tonic for the stomach, where another active ingredient, emodin, stimulates peristalsis, helping with constipation, although large overdoses may cause  nausea or diarrhea. It has even been shown to slow the growth of cancer.<br /><br />Its tannin content makes it astringent, and it\'s been used externally to stop the bleeding, most famously when Dr. Crusher had Capt. Picard apply a yellow taproot to her wound in an episode of \"Star Trek—The Next Generation.\"<br /><br />It also contains anthraquinones, good for ringworm and other fungal skin infections. In England, they rub the crushed leaves on cure nettle stings, while reciting: “Nettles in, dock out.”<br />','Never confuse curly dock with moe dock or larry dock!<br /><br /> Nyuk! Nyuk! Nyuk!','','','','',NULL,0,'0','',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(11,66,'Common Dandelion','*Taraxacum officinale*','Family *Asteraceae  (Compositae),* the astor or composite family','','The youngest leaves are good to eat in early spring, when they first appear, and in late fall, when new leaves emerge. The crowns and flower buds come up next, in early spring too, soon after, still in early spring the flowers are at their best, although some continue to bloom in the summer and fall.','Lawns, roadsides, meadows, cultivated areas, disturbed habitats','Worldwide','Look for a basal rosette of hairless, leaves with downward-pointing (toward the leaf base), large, jagged teeth, a slender, hairless, leafless, unbranched flower stalk, a yellow composite flower with ray flowers but no disk flowers, and a fluffy, white, spherical seed head with tiny brown seeds.','One of the best-known wild edibles and most hated lawn weeds, everyone recognizes the flowers, but getting the youngest, tasty leaves before the flowers appear takes a bit of attention.<br /><br />The jagged leaves grow from 3 to 12 inches long and 0.5 to 2.5 inches wide, always growing in a basal rosette. The leaves\' large teeth always point toward the leaf base, not outward or toward the leaf tip. The rosette’s immature, tightly-wrapped leaf bases just above the top of the root form a tight “crown”.<br /><br />Short, stubby, green, cylindrical flower buds form in the middle of the basal rosette before individual, smooth, green, slender flower stalks lift them 2 to 18 inches above the ground. The  yellow composite flowers, 1 to 2 inches wide, consist of ray flowers only. Reflexed green bracts bend under each flower. A flower head may change into the familiar, white, spherical seed head overnight. A tiny parachute connects to each tiny, brown seed, which is shaped like a sunflower seed.<br /><br />The thick, brittle, beige, branching, perennial taproot grows up to 10 inches long. All parts of this hairless plant exude a white milky sap when broken.<br />','Collect only the youngest leaves, when they first come up in early spring and late fall. They soon get very bitter, especially by the time they flower. Choose plants with the broadest leaves, which are the best, not the ones where most of the leaf consists of teeth.<br /><br />While you can certainly grab handfuls of leaves, cutting the root just under the center of the rosette with a pocketknife gets you the entire rosette or crown in a second, and while it\'s still intact, you can shake off most of the debris before bagging the plant.<br /><br />A serrated grapefruit spoon is even better than a pocket knife for scooping out the very young flower buds at ground level, in the center of the rosettes.<br /><br />You can easily collect the flowers by hand, but choose the most brightly colored, freshest, tastiest ones, especially abundant during the peak of the flowering period, in early spring, and use a knife to remove the bitter, green sepals.<br /><br />As with most roots, a shovel is the best implement for digging them up, relatively rock-free soil makes for the best places to dig, and periods when rain has loosened the soil are the best times to dig. ','Add the youngest leaves, crowns, flower buds, or flowers raw to salads. They\'re quite tasty, strongly flavored with a small overtone of bitterness. Use sparingly if the slight bitterness bothers you.<br /><br />Sautéing dandelion leaves or crowns shrinks them and concentrates this bitterness, but it miraculously vanishes if you cook them further in a sauce, especially if you include spices. I sauté them 10 minutes, then simmer another 10 minutes, using a cooking oil, spices, and sauce that come from the same culinary tradition. You can make a side dish this way, or include pasta, grain, bread cubes, or other sources of protein to make a dandelion-based entrée.<br /><br />After removing the sepals, you can sauté the flower buds or flowers too. They taste like carrots, so sautéeing the 2 vegetables together in olive oil, seasoned with mint and marjoram, plus a dash of white wine plus salt and pepper to taste, works especially well, where the carrots\' sweetness offsets the flowers\' slight bitterness. Or stir the flowers into pancake batter and cook on a griddle like you\'d cook pancakes, to make dandelion fritters. The flowers are also famous for making dandelion wine.<br /><br />Some people cook and eat the taproot. I\'ve found it too bitter and fibrous—way inferior to other wild root vegetables.','•Basal rosette of leaves with large teeth pointing toward the leaf base<br />•Familiar yellow composite flowers, each on 1 hollow, hairless flower stalk<br />•Spherical cluster of white parachutes attached to tiny, brown seeds<br />•A milky latex<br />•No hairs on any part of the plant','','The common dandelion has no poisonous look-alikes. You can use other similar but less widespread *Taraxacum* species the same way you\'d use the common dandelion.<br /><br />Other edible relatives, all with a white, milky latex, look very similar when young, but they\'re very different when they get older:<br /><br />Chicory\'s *(Cichorium intybus)* young leaves\' teeth don\'t always point to the leaf bases, and there\'s often a reddish color on the leaf midrib. When it gets older, it gets several feet tall, with blue flowers.<br /><br />Wild lettuce\'s *(Lactuca spp.)* leaves have at least some hairs, the leaf is triangular in cross section, it gets much taller than the dandelion, the flowers grow in groups, and it has fibrous roots.','The leaves have more beta-carotene, the precursor of vitamin A, than carrots, and more iron and calcium than spinach. They also provide vitamins B1, B2, B5, B6, B12, C, E, P, and D, biotin, inositol, potassium, phosphorus, magnesium, and zinc. The flower provides beta carotene as well. Oh, and, if I didn\'t already mention it, eating dandelions is good for you!','People have been drinking dandelion root tea, made by boiling 1 tbs. of the chopped root in 1 cup of water, as a tonic, since prehistoric times. It contains inulin, a polysaccharide that doesn\'t elicit an insulin response—good for diabetics and hypoglycemics. Due to the glycocide taraxacin, it\'s especially good for the liver and gallbladder, where it promotes the flow of bile, reduces inflammation of the bile duct, and helps get rid of gall stones. It’s good for chronic hepatitis, where it reduces liver swelling and jaundice, and it helps indigestion caused by insufficient bile.<br /><br />It\'s been used so commonly as a diuretic, for kidney problems, that kids in France used to secretly place the flowers in each others pockets and accuse each other of bedwetting, leading to the modern French name of the dandelion: pisenlit. (\"Lit\" means bed.)<br /><br />Dandelion root decoction should be avoided in cases of irritable stomach or bowel, or if there\'s acute inflammation.<br />','Eating the dandelion that grows just inside Central Park\'s West 81 St. entrance can be extremely dangerous, as exemplified by what happened after I ate 1 of its leaves at 4 PM, March 29, 1986:<br /><br />Turns out 2 undercover park rangers had infiltrated my foraging tour. They said they were married, and never held hands or kissed, so I believed them! The man took pictures, I held up the specimens for him, only I was the specimen. When I ate the dandelion, they radioed the other rangers with secret walkie-talkies. I was suddenly surrounded, handcuffed, searched (don\'t know if they were looking for weeds or \"weed\"), and brought to the Central Park police station, where they too fingerprints and mugshots, and searched my backpack. Fortunately, I had eaten all the evidence! They issued me a summons for criminal mischief for removing vegetation from the park because I ate the dandelion. I had to go to court, and could face a year in jail. But they then made a big mistake: They let me go.<br /><br />I went home and spent the next day on the phone notifying the press. The following morning, on my way to the newsstand, 5 cops came after me, but they all wanted my autograph! I was front page news around the country, and got on everything from CBS News to Letterman. When they took me to court, I served \"Wildman\'s\" 5-Boro Salad to reporters and passersby on the steps of the Manhattan Criminal Courthouse, and the press ate it up. After a 2nd round of media circus, the Parks Commissioner turned over a new leaf. He negotiated with me, dropped the charges, and hired me to lead foraging tours throughout the NYC parks system. I worked as a Parks Dept. naturalist for the next 4 years before leaving to resume freelance work after a new administration reneged on the negotiated agreement of the predecessors.','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(12,78,'Daylily','*Hemerocallis fulva*','Family: *Hemerocallidaceae*','','The shoots are in season in early spring, the flowers mainly in late spring and early summer, although a few bloom throughout the summer, and the tubers are in season all year.','Cultivated habitats, gardens, roadsides, river banks, parks, open woodlands, and meadows','Most of the US and southern Canada','Look for long, light green, sword-like basal leaves that become floppy when they get large, and rhizomes spreading from the plant\'s base ending in tubers.<br />Look for 6-petaled, orange, funnel-shaped flowers in late spring and early summer with 1 light yellow line running along the length of each petal, 6 pistils, and 1 stamen, growing atop a slender, leafless stalk.','This herbaceous perennial produces dense stands of large, showy, edible flowers and flower buds above a basal rosette of long, sword-shaped leaves that you can also eat when they first come up, plus tubers that are in season all year.<br /><br />The narrow, linear, basal leaves, which grow from 1 to 3 feet long and have parallel veins, flop over as they get longer. When the shoots first appear in early spring, the leaves grow mostly in the same plane, and unite into a short, whitish, base growing 1 to 2 inches above ground level. Fleshy light brown rhizomes under .25 inches in diameter spread from the base into the ground, each ending in a small, oblong light brown tuber about .75 inches long. The true roots emanate from the tubers.<br /><br />6 to 15 large, showy, orange, short-stemmed, upward-facing, funnel-shaped flowers branch from a leafless flower stalk that grows up to 4 feet tall. 3 reflexed petals, and 3 nearly-identical sepals, with grow to about 4 inches long. Their edges are ruffled, and a pale yellow line runs along each petal\'s length. 6 long, pollen-covered stamens surround a single longer pistil inside each flower.<br /><br />During the flowering period, cylindrical, yellow-orange flower buds, growing from 1.5 to 3 inches long just before they open, grow on the same short branches as the flowers, replenishing the flowers, which wither at the end of the same day that they open. Shriveled remnants of previous days flowers hang from some of the short  branches.<br /><br />Wild dayliles spread underground and don\'t make seeds.','One of the easiest renewable edible plants to harvest in quantity, you can pull off and bag handfuls of the shoots under 8 inches tall (6 inch tall shoots are the best), or cut them with a knife or shears. And you can break off the flower buds and flowers with your fingers, or dig up the tubers with a shovel or trowel.','Use the young shoots raw in salads or sandwiches, or steam, sauté, or stir-fry them, and add them to soups, stews, or casseroles. Virtually any cooking method works with them, and their tasty, string bean/onion flavor always shines through. They cook in 10 to 15 minutes. Use shoots under 8 inches tall. Larger ones become coarse, unpleasant to eat, and hard to digest.<br /><br />Cook the larger unopened flower buds in recipes that call for green beans. The flavor is similar, and they cook in about 15 minutes. You can also reconstitute the previous day\'s wilted flowers in soups, or purée them and use as a flavorful thickener.<br /><br />The flowers are sweet and hot-tasting. Don\'t eat the green bases of the flowers, which are somewhat acrid. Add the flowers to salads that you\'re going to eat the same day, before they do their Cinderella (or *Mission Impossible)* thing at night. Italian and Chinese cooks dip the flowers in batter and deep-fry them. They\'re also excellent in soups, sold, dried, as \"golden needles\" in Chinese grocery stores, to use in traditional hot-and-sour soup. You can stuff the fresh flowers with with dried fruit, nuts, and sweetened vegan cottage cheese mixed with sweet herbs, close them with toothpicks, and serve these stuffed daylilies as a fancy dessert at parties.<br /><br />You can also scrub and slice the smaller, firm tubers (the larger, older ones are terrible), and sauté them in olive oil with garlic, salt, and pepper, or add to soups, stews, or casseroles. They taste a little like nutty turnips. Because the tubers are small and labor-intensive to clean, I rarely bother with them.','•Sword-shaped leaves of the shoots arising from a cylindrical, whitish base.<br />•Rhizomes spreading into the soil from the base, ending in small, potato-like tubers<br />•A leafless flower stalk<br />•Yellow-orange, cylindrical flower buds<br />•Showy, orange flowers with 3 reflexed petals and 3 very similar sepals<br />•A pale yellow line running the length of the center of each petal and sepal<br />•6 stamens and 1 pistil in each flower','Irises *(Iris spp.)* and daffodils *(Narcissus spp.)* have sword-shaped leaves when young, making them resemble daylily shoots. Later on, u the flowers are different, and they don\'t have rhizomes spreading underground from the plant\'s base each ending in a tuber, so dig them up to make sure you have the right plant before eating the shoots. ','The tiger-lily’s *(Lilium tigruinum)* edible flowers are spotted, and its flower stalks bear leaves.<br /><br />Cultivated daylilies come in different colors, sometimes with multiple sets of petals and sepals, and these may even produce seeds. Although edible, they\'re not as tasty as the wild, orange variety.','No nutritional information about the shoots is available, but the flowers and flower buds provide beta carotene, vitamin C and iron, and the tubers provide protein and essential fatty acids.','An important herb in Chinese traditional medicine, an infusion made from the flowers is used to treat post-traumatic stress disorders, to cause forgetfulness concerning the traumatic event. Chinese herbalists also use it as a pain-killer, for fever, as a sedative, and for childbirth[240].<br /><br />The rhizomes and tubers have shown antimicrobial and anti-parasitical activity. They may even slow the growth of cancer, although research is needed to verify this.','About 1 out of 5o people can\'t tolerate daylilies, especially the tubers and shoots, more so if they eat them raw. These people experience diarrhea, sometimes with vomiting. Take a bite or 2 the first time you try them, and increase the amount by small increments in the following days. If you ever begin to feel queasy or nauseous, avoid this plant. (This caution doesn\'t apply if you\'re on a foraging tour that my wife\'s attending—she\'d be the 1-out-of-50 people.)<br /><br />Also, there are rare genetic variants, identical to other daylilies, that will cause such digestive distress for anyone who eats them. I\'ve led hundreds of tours since 1982 where we\'ve collected and eaten daylilies, and have never run into any of these varieties, so they must be extremely rare, but there\'s reliable documentation that this has occurred. Again, try 1 or 2 bites the first time you try daylilies from a new location, and avoid collecting from a stand if it makes you a little queasy.','','','','',NULL,0,'1','',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(13,88,'Epazote, Mexican tea','*Dysphania ambrosioides, Teloxys ambrosioides*','*Chenopodiaceae,* Goosefoot family','','Mid-spring through fall','Sunny habitats, roadsides, gardens, parks, disturbed soil','Native to Mexico and Central America, it grows across the US.','Look for a branching, medium-sized plant with long-oval, wavy-toothed leaves a strong, resinous smell, and tiny white-petaled flowers hidden in masses of green flower buds and fruits.','This fragrant, weedy-looking, branching plant, which grows 1 to 3 feet tall, is important as a culinary seasoning and medicinal herb.<br /><br />The wavy-toothed, 2 to 4 inches long leaves are oblong to lance-shaped, tapering at the base and tip. Clusters of tiny, inconspicuous, white, 5-petaled flowers hidden in masses of green flower buds, followed by masses of tiny, green fruits arise in spikes from the leaf axils of the top branches of this wind-pollinated plant.<br /><br />The whole glandular-dotted, slightly hairy plant has a strong, resinous fragrance. It smells like pine if you like it, or stinks like turpentine if you don\'t.','Strip off the leaves to use as a seasoning. If flowers or fruits come off too, that\'s fine. If the plant is very young, you can use the stems too, as long as they\'re not tough. And you can use the whole plant, except the roots, for making tea.','An important culinary herb in Mexican cuisine, you can use the fresh leaves, finely chopped, or the dried leaves, crumbled, to flavor bean dishes, soups, stews, or sauces. Use sparingly or the strong flavor, a little like tarragon, cilantro, and bay leaves, will overpower the other ingredients.<br /><br />Try add a teaspoon of fresh epazote or half a teaspoon of dried epazote to a couple of mashed avocados. Stir in some lemon juice, garlic, Tabasco sauce, fresh parsley, cumin, seasoned salt, and pepper, and you\'ll have a very tasty guacamole.<br /><br />Caution: Don\'t use epazote as a potherb. It\'s good for you in small quantities, but poisonous in large quantities.','•Branching, slightly hairy plant, 1 to 3 feet tall<br />•Alternate, wavy-edged, oblong to lance-shaped leaves 2 to 4 inches long<br />•Green masses of inconspicuous, white, 5-petaled flowers on spikes arising from the upper leaf axils<br />•Strong, resinous odor',NULL,'Lamb\'s-quarters is an edible plant people have confused with epazote, but it has diamond-shaped leaves that are whitish underneath, and virtually no odor.','There\'s no nutritional analysis available.','Loaded with biologically active compounds, this herb has been used for centuries in Mexico and Central America, as an infusion, to kill parasites, especially hookworm. It was even in the US pharmacopeia until it was replaced by synthetic drugs.<br /><br />It\'s also a carminative, good for indigestion and gas. I never cook beans without adding some epazote, especially before an indoor speaking engagement. A Nicaraguan man who attended one of my tours said it\'s name in his country translates to \"fart buster!\"','Don\'t use epazote as a potherb. It\'s good for you in small quantities, but poisonous in large quantities.<br /><br />Don\'t use the herb if you\'re pregnant or lactating, and don\'t take the essential oil (which you\'d have to buy, and is used externally for ringworm), extracted from the seeds, internally. It\'s considered toxic.<br /><br />Also, there are certain individuals who should never use epazote. It can make them sick or kill them, even in small amounts. Fortunately, you can tell who these individuals are by determining their occupation: Never use epazote if you\'re a lawyer or politician—it kills parasites!','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(14,94,'Field Pennycress','*Thlaspi arvense*','Family: *Brassicaceae* or *Cruciferae,* the mustard or cabbage family','','Spring and summer','Lawns, fields, meadows, roadside, disturbed habitats; requires full sunlight','Throughout most of North America','Look for hairless plant with alternate, lance-shaped leaves that clasp the stem, clusters of small, 4-petaled, white flowers, and flattened, circular, notched seed pods.','This is a common, tasty mustard has distinctive seed pods that look like notched pennies.<br /><br />A hairless European annual, the lance-shaped basal leaves, which arise from a taproot, grow 1 to 6 inches long. Sometimes lobed, with rounded tips, they disappear when the flower stalk emerges.  The lance-shaped, alternate stem leaves, with wavy margins, grow 0.5 to 3 inches long. Because they have no leafstalks, 2 lobes from the base of each leaf partially encircle or clasp the stems.<br /><br />Tiny, short-stalked, 4-petaled, white flowers grow in long, crowded clusters on racemes around the tips of the 6- to 18-inch-long ridged flower stalks, from mid-spring to mid-summer. The petals form a cross, typical of the mustard family. They’re followed by circular, flattened, heart-shaped, deeply notched seedpods reminiscent of pennies, which release tiny, dark brown seeds when they mature dry out.<br /><br />Crush the plant and you\'ll smell onions, ruining dairy products when cows eat it, so even though it\'s very tasty to foragers, farmers call it “stinkweed.”','Use a pocket knife to cut the rosette from the taproot, or harvest the basal leaves by hand. Strip leaves, flowers or seed pods, and tender pieces of the stems with your fingers.<br /><br />Collect the nearly mature seed pods and store them in a paper bag (which is porous) until they dry out, open up, and release the seeds. Spread on a try, blow away the chaff, and store the seeds in a tightly closed jar.','This is a very tasty, but fiery-hot mustard, a little like wasabe. Use the basal leaves, the leaves on the leafstalk, flowers, seedpods, and tender portions of the stems raw in salads or sandwiches, or cook using virtually any method about 10 minutes or until tender. Use sparingly unless you love spicy food.<br /><br />You can also make prepared mustard by grinding the seeds or green seedpods in a blender with vinegar to cover, plus salt or mellow miso, and turmeric (for yellow color) plus other spices, i.e., tarragon, white pepper, or garlic, typically used in making prepared mustard.<br /><br />Caution: Eating very large quantities of this plant make cause nausea or dizziness, or inhibit white blood cells, but the plant is way to spicy to eat in such quantity, and such problems have only been observed in cattle.<br /><br />If you\'re a kid, tell your friend the seeds are very sweet and feed some to him or her. You may lose a friend, but you\'ll laugh your head off!','•A basal rosette of hairless, lance-shaped leaves arising from a rhizome<br />•Lance-shaped, alternate leaves with a pair of pointed lobes at the base that clasp the stem.<br />•Racemes of tiny, white, 4-petaled flowers near the plant\'s tip.<br />•Flat, circular, notched seed pods containing tiny, black seeds<br />•An onion-like odor when crushed',NULL,'Other edible members of the mustard family have similar flowers, but the leaves are usually toothed or lobes and don\'t clasp the stem, and none has the notched, circular seed pods.','A good source of vitamin C, for a plant, the leaves are high in protein. They’re also a good source of B-complex vitamins and sulfur.','An infusion of the seeds acts as a tonic. Research has shown it to have anti-microbial properties, suppressing the growth of staphylococcus and streptococcus, and it\'s been used for fevers, coughs, and various infections. The whole plant is also a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory, like aspirin.<br />','','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(15,103,'Foxtail Grass','*Setaria spp.*','Family: *Poaceae (Gramineae), * true grasses','','Late summer and early fall','Sunny habitats, wild and cultivated fields, disturbed habitats, parks','Most of North America','Look for grass with a large, cylindrical flower head that resembles a fox\'s tail.','The flat, narrow, toothless, parallel-veined leaves of these annual or perennial grasses  grow up to 6 inches long. And the tiny flowers grow on a narrow, curved, unbranched, cylindrical flower heads in the summer. Small, black seeds replace them on the same bristly seed heads in late summer and autumn.<br /><br />One species,  yellow foxtail *(S. pumila), has an upright seed head, the other one, green foxtail *(S. viridis)* has a curved seed head.<br /><br />The roots are fibrous.','Wait until the seeds are ripe and fall off when you gently rub the seed heads. Do so over a paper bag with many seed heads. Spread on a tray and blow away any chaff with a fan later. Avoid unripe seed heads, and don\'t rub hard, or you\'ll get very annoying hairs that will get stuck between your teeth.','Foxtail grass has a pleasant, nutty flavor and very crunchy texture. Grind and use half-and-half with whole grain flours to make breads, pancakes, or porridge, or cook in grain dishes, 1 part foxtail grass seeds to 10 part whole grains, to add crunchiness and flavor. Unlike cultivated grains, foxtail grass seeds never become completely soft, an asset if you like crunchy foods.','•Unbranched, smooth-edged leaves up to 6 inches long<br />•Bristly, cylindrical seed heads, straight or curved, resembling a fox\'s tail',NULL,'Other grasses don\'t have bristly, cylindrical seed heads that look like a fox\'s tail.','Most grains provide protein, B-complex vitamins, and high-quality oils, but this close relative of millet has never been tested.','People have crushed the whole plant and applied it to bruises, and in Japan, people eat the cooked, ground seeds for digestive disorders. ','','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(16,108,'Garlic Mustard','*Alliaria petiolata*','Family: *Brassicaceae* or *Cruciferae,* the mustard or cabbage family','','Basal leaves and taproots: fall through early spring<br />Sprouts: early spring<br />Leafstalk leaves: mid-spring<br />Seeds: Mid-summer through mid-fall','Woodlands, disturbed habitats, parks, roadside, trailsides','Most of North America','Look for basal rosettes of long-stalked, coarsely-toothed, heart-shaped leaves in forests, or flower stalks with alternate, triangular to arrow-shaped leaves and racemes of small, white, 4-petaled flowers in mid-spring.','This common, healthful, invasive woodland biennial has a distinctive garlic smell when crushed, which helps protect it from insects (unless Italian insects find it!)<br /><br />Sprouts that look like alfalfa sprouts, each with a single, slender, reddish stalk around 2 inches tall, and a single, strap-shaped leaf around 0.5 inch long, grow from seeds at the same time you see basal rosettes coming from taproots of second-year plants. The long-stalked, scallop-edged, deeply-veined, kidney-shaped basal leaves grow up to 2½ inches across. The thin, white taproot smells and tastes like horseradish.<br /><br />By mid-spring, second-year plants grow a single erect flower stalk 1 to 3.5 feet tall, slightly hairy, with more pointed, alternate, deeply veined, larger-toothed, triangular leaves. A broccoli-like flower bud soon gives way to 4-petaled white flowers 1/3 inch across. Configured like a cross (typical of the mustard family), they also alternate around the flower stalk. They’re soon replaced by long, green, slender, 4-parted, cylindrical seedpods 1 to 1½ inches long, curving upward on short stalks.<br />When the second-year plant dies in the summer, the dry, light brown pods split lengthwise to reveal 2 rows of tiny, oblong, dark brown, finely lined, spicy flavored seeds.<br />','It\'s as easy to pull off handfuls of basal leaves with your fingers as it is to strip leaves, soft parts of the upper stems, flower buds, and flowers.<br /><br />If the soil is soft and moist, you can sometimes pull on the top of the taproot with your hand and remove it. Otherwise, use a shovel or trowel.<br /><br />Gently break off lots of dried seed head and transfer them into a supermarket paper shopping bag. By the time you get home, many of the seeds will have fallen out of the pods. Rub the pods with your hands to loosen the rest of the seeds, spread on a tray, and use a fan to blow the seeds into your sink. Store the seeds in a tightly closed glass jar. They last indefinitely (or until you use them.)','The leaves all taste like garlic, with bitter and spicy overtones. The young leaves on the developing flower stalk and the accompanying flower buds and flowers, which taste hot and sweet as well, are best, followed by the basal leaves in early spring, when the plant first experiences a growth spurt. Use them in any savory recipe. You can use any cooking method. They cook in about 5 minutes.<br /><br />The basal leaves are edible in the cold weather seasons, but have an overtone of bitterness that doesn\'t disappear when you sauté and cook in a sauce, which works with dandelions and its relatives. Use them sparingly in salads or sandwiches.<br /><br />This plant makes superb pestos, where even the bitterness of the cold weather season basal leaves disappears.<br /><br />Use the seeds to spice up anything you want. Unlike hard commercial mustard seeds, which you usually have to grind, these seeds are soft enough to chew, and they add texture as well as spiciness to any recipe. Since they burn when you sauté them, add them to recipes at the end of the cooking process if possible, to avoid dissipating any of their flavor, although they work quite well cooked, too, i.e., in place of caraway or poppy seeds in breads and rolls.<br /><br />Use the horseradish-flavored root just like horseradish, for extra spiciness, in any recipe. Like horseradish, the flavor is volatile—cooking destroys it. So add this at the end of a recipe, or use it raw as a garnish. To preserve the root, grate or finely chop it, cover it with vinegar, and refrigerate.','•Basal rosette of long-stalked, coarsely toothed, heart-shaped leaves<br />•Flower stalk 1 to 3.5 feet tall with triangular, coarsely toothed leaves, small, broccoli-like flower buds, and clusters of small, 4-petaled white flowers<br />•Many long, narrow seed pods with oblong, black seeds on dying plants<br />•Slender taproot that smells like horseradish<br />•Leaves, stem, flower buds, and flowers smell like garlic when crushed<br />',NULL,'Violet leaves, which are edible, look like young garlic mustard leaves, but with smaller teeth and no garlic odor.','Garlic mustard is a good source of vitamins A, C, and E, some of the B vitamins, plus potassium, calcium, magnesium, copper, iron and manganese. Like other mustards, it contains plant estrogens that are inert in humans (they\'re probably designed by natural selection to interfere with insects\' development), but block human and synthetic estrogens from promoting unwanted cell proliferation that can lead to cancer. The sulfur-containing amino acids that give it the garlic odor, like garlic, promote cardiovascular health. Pretty impressive for a despised invasive weed!','Not a major traditional medicinal plant, garlic mustard has been little used in herbal medicine, although an infusion of the leaves has been used as a diaphoretic to cause sweating, stimulate the immune system and treat bronchitis. People have heated the root in oil and applied this ointment to the chest for bronchitis too. I have no idea whether or not this works, but juice from the leaves does inhibit the growth of gram negative bacteria, which includes those that cause gastric enteritis and typhoid.<br /><br />People have also applied the crushed leaves to insect bites and stings, although I\'ve had such good results with jewelweed and common plantain that I\'ve never tried this.','Be careful not to let the seeds fall to the ground when you collect them, especially if you\'re Catholic (you\'re not supposed to spill your seeds!) ','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(17,119,'Japanese Knotweed','*Polygonum cuspidatum, Fallopia japonica*','Family: *Polygonaceae,* knotweed or smartweed family','','You can eat this plant only in early spring, while the shoots are tender. On very rare occasions, new edible shoots come up in the fall after the mature plants have been cut down.<br /><br />The inedible flowers bloom in the summer, the inedible seeds ripen in the fall, and the inedible dead stalks persist through the winter into the following spring.','Partial shade or full sunlight, disturbed habitats, roadsides, fields, and riverbanks','Throughout most of North America','In early spring, look for green shoots that resemble asparagus, but flecked with red, pink, and magenta, and divided by joints below sheathes. Look for them among the previous year\'s dead stems, which create conspicuous bamboo-like thickets.<br /><br />Later in the spring, and in the summer and fall, look for the 4 to 6 inch-long, alternate, toothless, pointed, 3-sided leaves, and lacy spikes of small white flowers or seeds.','This tall, bushy, bamboo-like invasive Asian perennial creates stands of reddish, bamboo-like shoots with a wonderfully sour flavor, in early spring.<br /><br />Growing 0.5 to 1.25 inches wide, the young, green shoots are dappled with red, pink, and magenta, beginning in the middle of early spring. Whitish, papery sheaths grow upward from regularly spaced joints. Later on, the tall, hollow, conspicuous, woody, jointed mature stems grow 9 to 12 feet tall create and create what looks like a bamboo thicket. The dead stalks persist through the winter and into the following spring.<br /><br />Shaped like bulging triangles, the alternate, pointed, toothless leaves, with flat bases and pointed tips, grow to 4 to 6 inches long and 2.5 to 4.25 inches wide.<br /><br />Hundreds of tiny, attractive-looking, greenish-white flowers grow on many long, lacy spikes in the summer, to be replaced by many tiny, 3-sided, smooth, beige, papery fruits in autumn. Each contains 1 tiny, hard, brown seed.<br /><br />An underground network of interconnected rhizomes is the bane of many gardeners\' existence.<br /><br /><br />','Break off the shoots near ground level, discard the inedible leaves, and bag. Those 6 to 8 inches tall are best—you can collect a lot in a very short period of time.<br /><br />Smaller ones are more labor intensive to collect, while larger shoots tend to get tough rinds, which you have to peel off. By the time the shoots reach 4 feet tall, only the tops are tender enough to peel and eat. Also, the flesh becomes thinner, so there\'s increasingly more work for less food until they become completely inedible in mid-spring.','Discard the leaves and chop or slice the young shoots, which are intensely sour. Use them sparingly in fruit dishes, to contrast the fruit\'s sweet flavor, similar to the way people use rhubarb, a relative. A 1 to 10 ratio works well. The shoots taste great in pies, cobblers, cakes, and pastries. Or incorporate a small proportion into applesauce.<br /><br />The shoots are also excellent in larger quantities as a sour addition to soups, stews, and casseroles, especially with bland ingredients, i.e., potatoes. And they\'re wonderful in ice creams and sorbets (similar to lemon sorbet), as well as puddings and jams.<br /><br />Before the larger shoots get tough, you can poke in a chopstick to punch through the membrane separating segments of the peeled shoots, insert a sweet or savory stuffing, and bake, with or without a sauce. Using Italian ingredients, I make Knot Ziti (no, I really did, and it\'s in my cookbook too, believe it or knot!)<br /><br />You usually discard the rinds of older shoots, but you can substitute them for orange rind and cook them in sweetened orange juice thickened with agar to make Knot Marmalade.','•Jointed shoots in early spring spotted with red, pink, and magenta<br />•Whitish sheaths above the joints<br />•Skeleton\'s of the previous year\'s growth of hollow, jointed, woody, bamboo-like stalks, persisting into the following spring<br />•Smooth-edged, bulging-triangular leaves, 4 to 6 inches long and 2.5 to 4.25 inches wide, with pointed tips and straight bases<br />•Long spikes of tiny, white flowers, followed by small, smooth, papery fruits, arising from the leaf axils',NULL,'Giant knotweed *(P. sachalinense)* is similar to Japanese knotweed, but bigger, and much less common. You use it the same way.<br />Asparagus *(Aspargus officinalis)* shoots have no sheathes or reddish flecks, and the leaves, flowers, and fruits are completely different.','Japanese knotweed shoots provide vitamins A and C, the antioxidant flavonoid rutin, and minerals potassium, phosphorus, zinc, and manganese. It’s also an excellent source of resveratrol, also found in the skin of red grapes and in red wine, which lowers LDL (bad) cholesterol, and reduces the risk of heart disease.<br /><br />','Large quantities may act as a gentle laxative, like rhubarb. This mucilaginous vegetable is very soothing to the stomach and intestines, and its mild acidity helps break up fat and stimulate digestion.<br /><br />In addition to lowering the risk of cardiovascular disease, Japanese knotweed\'s resveratrol may delay the onset of Alzheimer’s disease or slow its progression. Normally, glial cells in the brain support the neurons, but in Alzheimer’s disease, an accumulation characteristic amyloid plaques signal these helper cells to kill the neurons instead. The research is preliminary, but resveratrol seems to block this deadly signal.<br /><br />In addition, extracts of the plant have shown anti-tumour activity.','Don\'t eat large quantities of Japanese knotweed raw. It has much more oxalic acid than cooked knotweed, and this may cause problems. ','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(18,126,'Lady\'s Thumb','*Polygonum persicaria*','Family: *Polygonaceae,* knotweed or smartweed family','','Mid-spring through mid-fall','Full or partial sun, disturbed habitats, roadsides, parks, meadows, stream banks, railroads, gardens, lawns, and meadows—especially where there\'s low, wet ground.','Most of the US and Canada','Look for stands of medium-sized plants with alternate, lance-shaped leaves sometimes with a central chevron, a terminal cylindrical cluster of tiny, pink flowers, and a fringe of hairs above the nodes on the stems.','This especially common, easy to recognize edible plant with upright clusters of small, pink flowers, grows nearly everywhere.<br /><br />This European herbaceous annual usually grows 1 to 2.5 feet tall, and often creates dense stands.<br /><br />The branching plant\'s narrow, pointed, lance-shaped leaves get from 1.5 to 4.5 inches long. A slightly darkened triangular spot (chevron), the \"lady\'s thumbprint,\" often appears toward the leaf\'s center.<br /><br />Conspicuous terminal clusters up to 1.5 inches long, consisting of tiny, pink (sometimes white) flowers grow in dense, narrow racemes up to 1.5 inches long.<br /><br />Swollen, reddish-tinged nodes grow along the stem at regular intervals. A sheath connected to the very short, reddish leaf stalk wraps around the stem, and a fringe of very short hairs grows from the top of the sheath.<br /><br />This plant has both fibrous roots and a shallow taproot.<br />','Hold down bunches of plants with 1 hand and strip off the leaves with the other. You may want to discard the flowers. Most people don\'t care for them, although some people eat them, especially kids, who like the color. The stems are mostly too tough to eat.','Lady\'s thumb leaves are very mild-tasting. I tell young kids that they taste like lettuce, then suggest \"Lettuce try some,\" and they usually love them. Adults, on the other hand, often find them bland, sometimes suggesting that they\'re as tasteless as my jokes, but they go well in salads or sandwiches to contrast and offset the many strong-tasting wild greens.<br /><br />You can also sauté them with other more flavorful ingredients, or add them in soups, stews, and casseroles. They cook in about 10 minutes.','•A medium-sized plant with alternate, smooth-edged, lance-shaped leaves 1.5 to 4.5 inches long<br />•Narrow upper racemes of tiny pink flowers up to 1.5 inches long<br />•Stem usually close to 1.5 to 2.5 feet tall, divided by reddish-tinged nodes from which arises a sheath fringed with very short hairs.','Don\'t confuse lady\'s thumb with Lady\'s Fingers™! This junk food contains refined carbohydrates such as white flour and white sugar, plus artificial flavors and colors, which, when consumed in excess, contribute to the wide range of epidemic chronic illnesses so common in America today. Fortunately, Lady\'s Fingers™ grow only in supermarkets and convenience stores.','Lady\'s thumb is a member of the smartweed family, and other smartweeds, which are larger than lady\'s thumb and bear white or pink flowers, lack the characteristic fringe of very short hairs above the sheaths on the stems. Also called smartass or water pepper, these nonpoisonous plants may make you smarter—many are so acrid, they make your mouth smart so much that you\'ll become smart enough never to eat them again! Nevertheless, some people use them in small amounts in place of hot pepper. If you\'re daring, you may safely chew a bit of a leaf on the tip of your tongue before spitting it out, to see if you like the flavor (you probably won\'t!)','No information is available.','Although people tried using this plant inconsistently for disparate problems in the past, it never seems to have been especially valuable, and it isn\'t currently being used very much, if at all, in herbal medicine.<br />','','','','','',NULL,0,'1','',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(19,136,'Lamb\'s-quarters','*Chenopodium album*','Family: *Chenopodium,* the goosefoots family','','Leaves: Mid-spring through mid-fall<br />Seeds: Late fall','Rich soil, sunny or partially shaded habitats, disturbed habitats, roadsides, fields, agricultural land, edge habitats, parks','Throughout North America','Look for a large, branching, odorless plant with diamond-shaped leaves that are mealy white underneath, and dense spikes of tiny, green flowers toward the top branches.','This common, odorless European annual, with many branching stems is one of our best wild vegetables. It usually grows from 3 to 5 feet tall, (sometimes up to 10 feet), with slender, grooved stems often tinged with red—especially next to the leaf axils.<br /><br />The alternate, diamond-shaped, wavy toothed mature leaves grow up to 4 inches long. They\'re mealy whitish underneath. The youngest leaves, on the other hand, are linear, and white all over. The leaf stalks grow to about half the length of the leaves.<br /><br />Tiny, green, inconspicuous, bad-tasting, ball-like flowers grow in short, dense spikes in the upper leaf axils, and at the plant’s tip, in summer and fall, eventually turning reddish-brown. By late fall, as many as 75,000 tiny, shiny, black seeds grow inside.<br /><br />Caution: Sometimes the leaves are blotched with red. This indicates insect damage. There\'s even a tiny leaf miner that burrows between the top and bottom surface of the leaves. Don\'t eat these marred leaves, especially if you\'re a vegetarian! Also, avoid plants growing in soil polluted with nitrates, which they can pick up and pass on to you, causing nitrate poisoning.','1. Leaves: Pinch of the whole very young plant while it\'s a few inches tall and the stem is still tender enough to break easily. Strip off the leaves of older plants with your fingers.<br /><br />2. Seeds: Compared to amaranth *(Amaranthus spp.), it\'s more difficult to get a good harvest of these seeds, so look for the dead plants where they\'re tall and very abundant. Clip off large numbers of seed clusters with kitchen scissors, pruning shears, or a pocket knife. Put them in paper supermarket shopping bags and let them dry out a couple of weeks if necessary (you can store them indefinitely this way).<br /><br />Rub the dry seed heads (this works with fresh seed heads too, but it\'s less efficient) over a bowl to loosen the seeds. Transfer them to a tray or cookie sheet and blow a fan across the tray over a sink, or outdoors, to get rid of the chaff. Use the seeds immediately, or store indefinitely in tightly closed jars.','1. Leaves: Lamb\'s-quarters leaves taste somewhat like its relative, spinach. Use them, and very young whole plants, like spinach—raw, sautéed, steamed, simmered in soups, baked in quiches, or in any recipe that calls for raw or cooked greens.<br /><br />2. Seeds: Cook the nutty flavored seeds as you would a grain: Boil them in water to cover for about 15 minutes, or until the water is absorbed and the seeds are soft, like rice. You may use soy-, nut-, or oat milk instead of water, plus fresh or dried fruit, sweet herbs (i.e., mint, cinnamon, ginger), and a sweetener, to make a sweet hot cereal. To make the seeds more nutty tasting, toast them in a pan over medium until they pop, stirring very often, before adding the liquid.','•Branching plant 3 to 5 feet tall or more<br />•Diamond-shaped, coarsely toothed mature leaves with mealy white undersides<br />•Young leaves linear, glistening white all over<br />•Dense spikes of small, green, spherical flowers on the upper leaf axils<br />•Dense spikes of small, green, spherical fruits filled with tiny black seeds, on the upper leaf axils<br />•Virtually no odor<br />','Epazote (*Dysphania ambrosioides, Teloxys ambrosioides*) is edible when used as a seasoning, but poisonous when eaten in large quantities, as you would with lamb\'s-quarters. However, although it branches and its flower clusters look similar to lamb\'s-quarters\', its strong, resinous odor alone will distinguish it from the nearly odorless lamb\'s-quarters. Also, its leaves are oblong to lance-shaped, without powdery-white undersides, unlike lamb\'s-quarters\' diamond-shaped leaves with powdery white undersides.','Lamb\'s-quarters has some similar-looking, edible relatives that you can use the same way as lamb\'s-quarters:<br /><br />1. Strawberry blight *(C. capitatum)* has more triangular leaves than lambs-quarters’—sometimes even arrow shaped, with more of the rounded flowers, and mild-flavored, bright red fruits.<br /><br />2. Poverty weed *(Monolepsis nuttalliana)* is a fleshy, branching, sprawling annual that grows up to 1 foot tall, with lance-shaped, alternate, mealy-textured leaves about 0.5 to 2.5 inches long, usually irregularly toothed but sometimes smooth, with a pair of lobes at the bases. Its brown fruits are flattened. It grows in alkaline or dry soil from the eastern edge of the Great Plains to California, and from Southern Canada to Mexico.<br /><br />3. Orache *(Atriplex patula)* is a salty tasting edible that grows near the seashore and in salty, alkaline soil throughout the country, with arrow-shaped instead of diamond-shaped leaves. Much touted by other authors, I\'ve always found it to have an unpleasantly bitter aftertaste. Maybe this uninspiring plant is better cooked, or other *Atriplex* species taste better. Or maybe all the non-foraging botanist who wrote foraging books never tried it!','Lamb\'s-quarters leaves provide more vitamin A, calcium, potassium, and iron than anything you can buy. They also contain B-c0mplex vitamins and vitamin C, as well as many trace minerals.<br /><br />The seeds provide protein,  calcium, phosphorus, potassium, and niacin.','This is not a medicinal plant.','Epazote (*Dysphania ambrosioides, Teloxys ambrosioides*) is edible when used as a seasoning, but poisonous when eaten in large quantities, as you would with lamb\'s-quarters. However, although it branches, and its flower clusters look similar to lamb\'s-quarters\', its strong, resinous odor alone will distinguish it from the nearly odorless lamb\'s-quarters. Also, its leaves are oblong to lance-shaped, without powdery-white undersides, unlike lamb\'s-quarters\' diamond-shaped leaves with powdery white undersides.','','','','',NULL,0,'0','',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(20,147,'Mugwort','*Artemisia vulgaris*','Family *Asteraceae  (Compositae),* the astor or composite family','','Food: Early spring<br />Tea: Early spring through late fall','Sunny and partially shaded habits, nitrogenous soil, disturbed habitats, old fields, meadows, roadsides, ditches, parks, edges, and thickets','Eastern North America, southern Canada, the Pacific Northwest, and California','Look for dense stands of tall plants (or a ground cover where it\'s been mowed) with deeply cut lower and linear upper leaves, whitish underneath, and fragrant when crushed.','Growing from 2 to 12 feet tall, with a stem often tinged with red and purple that becomes somewhat woody, this very common, downy, fragrant, Eurasian colonial perennial takes over sunny, open areas anywhere it\'s been introduced.<br /><br />The pointed, alternate, stalked, toothed, mature leaves, dark green on top, are covered with mats of tiny, whitish hairs underneath. 2  to 4 inches long and 1 to 3 inches wide, they look a little like parsley—partially divided and subdivided many times, as though snipped with scissors. The upper leaves are less divided, sometimes linear, and often stalkless.<br /><br />Many tiny, green, cottony flowers, sometimes reddish-brown at the tips, grow on long, upright, leafy panicles, in the summer and fall. The tiny green fruits, which look like the flowers, release tiny seeds attached to tiny, white parachutes into the air, like dandelions, which also belong to the same family.<br /><br />The root system consists of woody rhizomes that secrete herbicides to kill competitors, ensuring that mugwort often grows in monocultures of dense stands.','To use as food, pinch off the young plants with your fingers. For tea or dreaming, break or clip off any above-ground parts of the plant.','This is a bitter relative of wormwood and not the best-tasting of wild foods. Nonetheless, Korea people dip the young leaves in batter when the plants are but a few inches tall, and deep-fry this. In China and Japan, it\'s used to flavor rice cakes, and in Japan, it\'s used in soba (buckwheat) noodles.<br /><br />You can also stuff a pillow with the soft parts of the plants. It gives some people vivid dreams, although they may or may not be pleasant.','•Dense stands of medium-sized to tall plants with deeply lobed, stalked mature leaves, and linear immature leaves<br />•Persistent woody skeletons of previous years\' growth<br />•Leaves with tiny, matted, whitish-green hairs underneath<br />•Many tiny greenish flowers growing on long, upright spikes<br />•A strong odor like tarragon and camphor when crushed',NULL,'Common ragweed *(Ambrosia artemisiifolia*) looks a little like mugwort, but its leaves are more finely dissected, it\'s not fragrant, and the leaves aren\'t light-colored underneath.<br /><br />Chrysanthemums *(Chrysanthemum spp.)* look a little like mugwort, but their leaves are much larger, they\'re not light green underneath, they only grow in gardens, and they have large, showy flowers.','There\'s no information available.','A major herb in traditional Chinese medicine, mugwort contains the fragrant, volatile oil psilostachyin, as well as biologically active ketones and alkaloids. Dried mugwort leaves and roots are used for moxa treatments, where it\'s burned in cups placed over acupuncture points. And it\'s served with fatty meals in China and Eastern Europe, to stimulate the secretion of bile to help digest the fat. The Chinese also use an infusion or tincture of the leaves and roots for anxiety, stress, insomnia, mild depression, irritability, restlessness, and menstrual problems—taken twice a day starting a week before menstruation, a strong infusion of the leaves greatly reduces or eliminates PMS symptoms and cramps. I can attest the this personally: Ever since I learned this plant, I\'ve never had a cramp!<br /><br />','Mugwort contains the controversial substance thujone, a possible hallucinogen well-known for its presence in notorious alcoholic beverage, absinthe, made with mugwort\'s relative, absinthe wormwood *(A. absinthium)*. So many deaths were attributed to absinthe in the late 19th and early 20th centuries that it had been banned worldwide. Nowadays those deaths are attributed to plain old alcoholism, because there\'s too little thujone in absinthe to cause poisoning, and the \"green fairy\" is legal again. Furthermore, mugwort is so bitter, it\'s unlikely anyone could possibly consume enough to cause harm.<br /><br />Mugwort is also closely related to ragweed *(Artemesia spp.)* Avoid it if you have hay fever or are allergic to ragweed.','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(21,153,'Pineapple Weed','*Matricaria matricarioides*','Family *Asteraceae  (Compositae),* the astor or composite family','','Mid-spring through summer.','Sunny places with poor soil, lawns, parks, gravel roads, walkways, baseball diamonds, cracks in sidewalks, and parking lots','Most of the US and southern Canada','Look for small plants with feathery leaves and small, flattened cones of yellow-green composite flowers, growing in very poor, sunny soil. Smell for pineapple.','This small, pineapple-scented plant, usually growing only 3 to 12 inches tall, bears very finely divided, hairless, fern-like, alternate leaves 0.5 to 2 inches long.<br /><br />The globular, yellow-green, bluntly cone-shaped, button-like, stalked, composite flower heads grow 0.25 to 0.5 inches across. They\'re borne in a cup of overlapping bracts on short flower stalks arising from the axils of the upper leaves. The flowers consist of many tiny, tightly packed disk flowers, best viewed under magnification. There are no ray flowers.<br /><br />The fruits are sunflower seed-like achenes, nearly too small to see.<br /><br />The root system consists of a  taproot with secondary fibrous roots.<br />','Snip the above-ground parts of this tough plant with scissors or a pocket knife. It\'s hard to break off with your fingers, and you don\'t want the roots or their accompanying soil','You can add some of the young leaves or flower heads, before they get bitter, to salads, sandwiches, or puddings, where they impart a pleasant pineapple flavor. But the most important use is as a great-tasting infusion. You can use all above-ground parts for this, made from fresh or dried plants.','•Small plant with feathery, fern-like leaves<br />•Thrives in full sunlight in very poor soil<br />•Flattened cone-shaped, yellow-green, composite flowers the size of a pencil eraser<br />•No ray flowers<br />•Clear pineapple fragrance when crushed or torn<br />','','Some obstinate people insist that pineapple weed is chamomile *(M. recuttia),* a close relative with the same uses. Both plants have similar leaves, but chamomile\'s a larger plant, with a larger disk that\'s yellow, not yellow-green. But to really convince the pig-headed, you\'ll have to point out that chamomile has white ray flowers, which pineapple weed lacks.','No nutritional information is available.','This is the tea to drink when you\'ve had a really bad day—a strong infusion is excellent for stress-related nervousness, gastric upset, and insomnia. A vegetarian alternative to counting sheep, it will settle a nervous stomach and calm you down enough to improve your chances of falling asleep.<br /><br />It has also been used to relieve infected sores, and for fevers, and postpartum anemia, although none of these uses have been scientifically verified.','Some people are highly allergic to this plant. Avoid it if you have hay fever, or are allergic to its relative, ragweed *Artemisia spp.)*','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(22,158,'Pokeweed','*Phytolacca americana*','Family: *Phytolaccaceae,* the pokeweed family','','Shoots: Mid-spring<br /><br />Berries for medicinal purposes: Mid-summer through fall','Partially shaded habitats or full sun, disturbed habitats, roadsides, meadows, fields, pastures, open woods, edge habitats','Eastern US, the West Coast, and all the southern states','Look for a plant with toothless, oval, medium-sized, alternate leaves, a purple-tinged, stout, upright stalk, and drooping racemes with either medium-sized, white, 5-parted flowers, or dark purple, slightly indented berries.','This large, stout, smooth, widely branching, purple-tinged, native perennial grows from 4 to 9 feet tall, and dies to the ground in the winter, leaving a whitish skeleton that overwinters.<br /><br />In mid-early spring, the young reddish-tinged, stout, unbranched shoot grows to about 1 inch thick. The oval, toothless, alternate leaves wrap around the stem and point upward at first.<br /><br />Later in the spring, the elliptical, entire, stalked, alternate, emerald-green leaves grow form 8 to 12 inches long, and 2.5 to 5 inches wide. They\'re sometimes mottled by a plant mosaic virus.<br /><br />Growing on drooping, 6 to 8 inch long, terminal racemes, the stalked, radially-symmetrical flowers grow to about 0.5 inch across, each with a green central ovary, 10 stamens, and 5 petal-like white sepals, but no true petals. They bloom from summer to fall.<br /><br />After the sepals fall off in late summer or fall, the ovary enlarges and becomes a shiny, dark, purple, juicy, stalked berry 0.33 inch across, composed of 5 to 12 segments fused into a ring. Each berry, filled with tiny, hard seeds, is indented on both ends, as though poked. The magenta raceme droops with the weight of the berries.<br /><br />The fleshy, light tan, perennial taproot can become enormous over the years.<br />','Break off the shoots no taller than 8 inches with your hands, in mid-spring only. Be absolutely certain that you haven\'t accidentally harvested any pieces of the poisonous taproots!<br /><br />Collect the berries for medicinal purposes when they\'re dark purple and juicy, from mid-summer through fall.','The puffer fish *(Tetraodontidae)* of the vegetable kingdom, this plant has an indescribably delicious flavor if prepared properly, deadly if not. Set up 2 pots of rapidly boiling water, a medium-sized cooking pot and a large reserve pot. Never use cold water.<br /><br />Rinse the pokeweed shoots and chop into bite-sized pieces. Boil 1 minute in the medium-sized pot, drain in a colander, return to the cooking pot, cover with more boiling water from the reserve pot, boil another minute, drain again, return to the cooking pot, pour in more boiling water, and boil until the pokeweed\'s been boiled a total of 15 to 20 minutes. This is necessary to be sure you\'ve removed all the poisons, which are water-soluble. Drain thoroughly in a colander, pressing the pokeweed against the colander\'s sides with a large wooden or slotted spoon, so it isn\'t soggy.<br /><br />Alth0ugh you could certainly serve the boiled pokeweed with a dash of olive oil and salt and pepper to taste, it\'s especially delicious with more seasonings. For example, you could lightly sauté some chopped garlic in olive oil until lightly browned (be carefully not to overcook the garlic, or it will become very bitter) and stir that into the drained, hot pokeweed, along with some tamari soy sauce (the high-quality soy sauce sold in health food stores). Or choose a different oil and matching seasonings from any of the world\'s many great cuisines.','•Stout, reddish, upright shoot with medium-sized, alternate, entire, elliptical leaves, in mid-spring<br />•Large, broadly branching herbaceous plant with curved racemes of small flowers, each with a green, central, button-like ovary surrounded by 5 white, petal-like sepals, in late spring and early summer<br />•Drooping, magenta raceme of purple, stalked berries, each slightly indented at the tip, from mid-summer through fall, containing several small, hard seeds<br />•Very large, light tan taproot',NULL,'Anyone who confuses the term poke *sallet* (an old English word for *cooked* vegetable) with poke *salad* is in for a surprise tour of the emergency room. This is not a food for people on a raw food diet!','Pokeweed is a great source of vitamin A, a fat-soluble vitamin that\'s not destroyed by boiling. Other vitamins and minerals are certainly dissipated by boiling.','Some people have successfully staved off arthritis by drinking 1 cup of an infusion per day made with 1 pokeberry, although this hasn\'t been verified (or disproven) scientifically. Since arthritis probably has varying causes, if this works, it may work for some people and not others.<br /><br />Phytolaccosides from leaves the leaves and pokeweed an antiviral protein are being researched for use against AIDS, and pokeweed\'s oleanolic acid has been shown to have anti-cancer properties in solid tumors and leukemia, but these substances have not been developed into something people can use safely or reliably yet.<br />the Native Americans, for malignant breast tumors. However, the root is also very caustic, and even if it were to slow the growth of the tumor, it\'s the cells that that have spread to other locations in the body which cause death, so this dangerous procedure should be avoided. ','Although none of the hundreds of people attending my tours every year since 1982 has ever gotten sick from eating this plant prepared according to my directions, this is still not a plant for unsupervised beginners. Pokeweed contains phytolaccatoxin and related triterpene saponins, an alkaloid called phytolaccin, plus histamines. Even if you don\'t know what these substances are, they can kill you: Poisoning causes burning of mouth and throat, salivation, severe stomach irritation, vomiting, bloody diarrhea, spasms, and convulsions. Without prompt medical attention, the accompanying severe dehydration can lead to death.<br /><br />Never eat pokeweed raw, never eat the roots, flowers, or seeds; use only shoots no more than 8 inches tall, during springtime only. Never eat pokeweed when it\'s in flower, or getting close to flowering, when the concentration of poisons skyrockets. Cook only as directed above. Make sure you don\'t accidentally include any pieces of the highly toxic root when you collect the shoots.<br /><br />Although some people have reportedly gotten away with eating the berries (which aren\'t even supposed to be tasty), they\'re dangerous too, and should be avoided Also, the seeds inside the berries are highly toxic.  ','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(23,167,'Poor Man\'s Pepper','*Lepidium virginicum*','Family: *Brassicaceae* or *Cruciferae,* the mustard or cabbage family','','Early spring to late fall','Sunny habitats, lawns, gardens, parks, disturbed habitats, fields, meadows, roadsides','Throughout the US plus eastern and western Canada ','In early spring and fall, look for basal rosettes of deeply lobed or toothed leaves with no colored sap, and teeth mostly pointing toward the leaf tip. From mid-spring to fall, look for a medium-sized plant with flower- and seed stalks resembling bottle brushes; tiny, white, 4-petaled flowers; and small, flat, nearly circular, very slightly notched seed pods.','This small to medium-sized, spicy-flavored, exotic annual grows 6 inches to 3 feet tall, beginning with a basal rosette in early spring. The narrow, stalked, lobed basal leaves grow 2 to 5 inches long. The basal leaves soon exchange their lobes for deep, sharp teeth that usually point toward the leaf tips. The rosette disappears when the plant flowers, so people who recognize it at one stage often have to re-learn what it looks in its other form.<br /><br />Resembling a bottle brush, a long, wiry, branching flower stalk grows from the rosette\'s center from mid-spring to fall, with similar but smaller alternate, linear to lance-shaped, toothed leaves tapering toward the base. There\'s usually no leaf stalk.<br /><br />From spring to fall, many tiny, short-stalked flowers 1/8 inch across, each with 4 white petals configured like a cross (typical of the mustard family), bloom at the tips of the branches, on racemes. In the summer and fall, they’re replaced from the bottom up by many small, flat, circular-to-ovate, short-stalked seed pods, very slightly notched at the tips, growing 1/8 inch across. Tiny yellow-brown seeds fall out as the plant dies and the seed pods turn white. The white skeleton often persists into the winter.<br /><br />There\'s no colored sap when you break open the plant, which has a short, slender, white  taproot. ','Although you can certainly tear off the basal leaves with your fingers, it\'s much more effective to sweep a pocket knife under the rosette to sever the root and gain the entire rosette. Then you can shake off the debris and bag the plant.<br /><br />Strip off the leaves, seed pods, and flowers (the wiry stem is too tough to eat) with any tender parts of the stem\'s top. This is easier if you proceed from the top to the bottom of the stem.','Poor man\'s pepper is one of the best-tasting mustards around, with a peppery flavor (what else would you expect?) a little like radish, horseradish, and wasabe. The chopped leaves, as well as the seeds and flowers, are great added raw to salads and sandwiches, or cooked for 10 minutes like any other greens, in soups, stews, casseroles, sauces, or virtually any savory dish.<br /><br />You can even roll the chopped plant into a sheet of toasted nori (a seaweed available in health food or Asian grocery stores) with cooked rice and vegetables, to make *vegetarian sushi* (don\'t forget to include a few pieces of a chopped vegetarian!)<br /><br />The seeds are too small to use, but you can make prepared mustard with the seed pods. Cover them with a mild vinegar in a blender, and purée with turmeric (for color) and garlic, plus mellow miso (available in health food stores) for texture. Other spices, such as those on label of your favorite prepared mustard, i.e., tarragon or lemon rind, are optional.<br /><br />You could even eat the taproot, but it\'s too small to be worth it.','•Basal rosette of lobed or toothed leaves, no colored sap<br />•Teeth on all leavespointing mostly toward the leaves\' tips<br />•Bottle brush-like branched flower stalk up to 3 feet high<br />•Tiny, white, 4-petaled flowers<br />•Small, flat, nearly circular to ovate seed pods, slightly notched at the tips',NULL,'This plant is in the mustard family, not related to pepper. It\'s sometimes called peppergrass, but this is its subgroup. Other similar edible peppergrasses include field pennycress *(Thlaspi arvense)* and field peppergrass or cow cress *(L. campestre).* They have larger seed pods, and leaves that clasp the flower stalk.<br /><br />Shepherd’s purse *(Capsella bursa-pastoris)*, another edible relative, has lobed leaves pointing outward that clasp the stem, no sharp teeth, and heart-shaped rather than circular seedpods.<br /><br />Unrelated dandelions *(Taraxacum officinale)*, chicory *(Cichorium intybus),* and wild lettuce *(Lactuca spp.)* have white, milky sap, and their leaves\' teeth never point to the leaf tips.','The leaves provide vitamin C, calcium, iron, and potassium.','An infusion of the leaves has been used for diabetes, to expel intestinal worms, as a diuretic, and to reduce the pain of arthritis. An infusion of the seed pods has been used to help expel phlegm for coughs and asthma, and to alleviate the accumulation of liquid in the chest. None of these uses has been verified scientifically.','This plant may be too spicy for young children.','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(24,176,'Purslane','*Portulaca oleracea*','Family: *Portulacaceae,* the purslane family','','Summer','Sunny habitats, very poor soil, lawns, gardens, fields, meadows, and cracks in the sidewalk','Throughout most of the US and Canada','Look for a prostrate plant with a thick, smooth, succulent, purple-red stem and stalkless, paddle-shaped leaves, growing in sunny places with very poor soil.','This sprawling, stalkless, smooth, thick succulent\'s purple-red stem grows 4 to 10 inches long and up to 6 inches tall. With its fleshy, alternate or opposite, stalkless, paddle-shaped leaves, 0.5  to 2 inches long, it provides foragers everywhere with an abundant supply of tasty, nutritious food every summer.<br /><br />Blooming from mid-summer to late summer, inconspicuous, tiny, yellow flowers only 1/5 inch wide, with 5 petals and 2 sepals, hide in the leaf axils or the tips of the branches, and open only on sunny mornings.<br /><br />Ovoid fruit capsules replace the flowers in late summer. Up to ¼ inch long, they split in half when they\'re ready to spill their tiny, hard, roundish, black seeds, the size of poppy seeds,<br /><br />Purslane has a taproot and many fibrous secondary roots.<br />','Simply break off the stems and bag them with the leaves, discarding any especially thick stems if they appear somewhat woody. The seeds, although edible, are far too few and too small to bother with.','Chop the leaves and stems and add them to salads and sandwiches. The mild sweet-sour flavor and crunchy texture make purslane idea for virtually any cooking method, and great in any kind of vegetable dish or entrée. It cooks in about 10 to 15 minutes.<br /><br />Because it\'s mucilaginous, it will thicken soups, stews, and sauces the way okra does. You may even set aside the leaves, which would fall off, and pickle the stems. ','•Sprawling succulent with thick, smooth, purple-red stems<br />•Fleshy, stalkless, paddle-shaped leaves<br />•Tiny, hidden, yellow flowers, opening only on sunny summer mornings<br />•Tiny ovoid fruit capsule splitting in half to release black seeds the size of poppy seeds.','Spurge (*Euphorbia spp.)* doesn\'t look that much like purslane. It does sprawl along the ground, but it has elliptical, not paddle-shaped leaves, the stem is wiry, not succulent, the flowers are white, and it exudes a sickly looking white sap when cut. But because it often grows side-by-side with purslane, this acrid poison could accidentally wind up in your bag if you\'re not wary.',NULL,'One of the most nutritious foods on the planet, purslane contains more omega-3 fatty acids, especially alpha-linolenic acid, than any other plant. It\'s aslo an excellent source of icosapentaenoic acid  (EPA).<br /><br />Purslane\'s provides vitamins A and C, and some vitamin-complex B and carotenoids, plus the minerals magnesium, calcium, potassium and iron.','Purslane is used to treat infections or uro-genital bleeding, as well as dysentery, in traditional Chinese medicine. The fresh herb has also been applied topically for skin sores, and insect and snake bites. Eating it also greatly reduces the symptoms of oral lichen planus, an autoimmune disease of unknown causes that effects the mouth\'s mucus membranes.','','','','','',NULL,0,'1','',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(25,182,'Red Clover','*Trifolium pratense*','Family: *Fabaceae,* the pea family','','Leaves: Early spring<br />Flowers: They\'re at their peak in late spring, although you can still find a few good ones in the summer and fall.','Sunny places, meadows, pastures, open fields, roadsides, lawns, parks, disturbed habitats','Throughout most of North America','Look for medium-sized, rounded flower heads on lawns and in meadows, composed of many tiny, narrow, 2-sided magenta fl0wers, set above a slender, branching flower stalk with alternate, 3-parted, palmate compound leaves.','Usually upright, parts of this well-known plant, which grows from 6 to 24 inches tall, may also creep along the ground, producing stems and fibrous roots at nodes.<br /><br />The alternate, palmate-compound leaves arise from a long, slender, downy, branching stem. The 3 oval to elliptical leaflets, 0.5 to 0.25 inches long and half as wide, all have a central seam that makes them look like they were folded in half, and they\'re all marked with a *V*-shaped chevron.<br /><br />Up to 60 tiny, bilateral-symmetrical, magenta, pea-like flowers, which grow up to 0.5 inch long, are crowded onto rounded flowerd head 1 inch across, at the tops of the stems.<br /><br />The seeds in the dry flower heads are very tiny and brown.<br />','Pick the young leaves and the flower heads by hand. If you\'re using the flowers for tea, including a few mature leaves won\'t do any harm<br /><br />The best time to collect the flowers is when the greatest number of plants have come into full flower at the same time, and most of the flowers are brightly colored, usually in late spring. Collect only the most attractive-looking flower heads. These are the best. Avoid those that still include some immature, green flowers, and those with brown, withered flowers. They\'re terrible. Leave those for the health food stores, which sell brown dried herbs that must have been picked as they were going bad, since freshly dried herbs retain their color.','You can add a few of the youngest leaves, raw, to salads, but they\'re hard to digest. It\'s much better to cook them like other greens, for about 15 minutes. They\'re not one of my favorite vegetables, with a raw string bean/turnip flavor, but some people like them.<br /><br />Red clover infusion has been popular since prehistoric times. Remember to use only the most brightly colored flower heads, which are the best quality. You can also pull the flowers off the flower heads with your fingers and add them (the flowers, not your finger!) raw, to salads. Or cook the flowers in virtually any dish that calls for vegetables. They cook in about 10 to 15 minutes. Although somewhat fibrous, they taste like sweet snap peas. I also like showering them, raw, onto ice cream, where they make colorful, sweet sprinkles.<br /><br />You can also dehydrate them, grind them into powder in a blender in a blender, and use them to supplement the protein of whole grains in breads and muffins. This works for the completely brown, dry flower heads, which contain the seeds, too, although they\'re not as tasty as the flowers. Add the meal of either to whole-grain flour to use in breads, pancakes, and muffins.','•Medium-sized herbaceous plant with alternate, 3-parted, palmate-compound leaves growing on a slender stem<br />•Roundish, magenta flower head packed with many long, narrow flowers<br />•Oval to elliptical leaflets with a midrib running down the their length, creating a seam<br />•A *V*-shaped chevron on each leaflet',NULL,'White clover *(T. repens)*, also edible, resembles red clover, but it\'s smaller, the flowers and leaves arise from separate stems, and the flowers are white, not magenta.<br /><br />People confuse wood sorrel *(Oxalis spp.)* with clover, but this edible plant has heart-shaped leaves and completely different flowers.','Red clover flower tea provides vitamin C, vitamin E, niacin, and thiamine, plus the minerals calcium, chromium, magnesium, niacin, phosphorus, and potassium.','One of the most widely used medicinal herbs, an infusion has a calming on some people. It\'s been used for menopause for centuries (scientific results concerning this use have been mixed), and it provides isoflavones such as genistein, irilone and pratensein, which act on estrogen receptors. Although drinking red clover tea regularly may lower the risk of breast cancer, it could also paradoxically stimulate an established malignant breast tumor\'s growth, and should be avoided for people with a history of this disease, as well as for women with estrogen-sensitive conditions such as endometriosis, ovarian cancer, uterine cancer, or uterine fibroids. Pregnant and lactating women should also avoid it.<br /><br />It may also be helpful for heart disease, but again the scientific evidence is mixed. On the other hand, preliminary research supports its use for osteoporosis.<br /><br />The infusion has also been used for other cancers, bronchitis, burns, ulcers, and asthma, and an ointment has been used for eczema and psoriasis, but these uses still need to be tested.','Eating too many mature leaves may cause a fatal disease called *the bloat,* if you\'re a cow!','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(26,186,'White Clover','*Trifolium repens*','Family: *Fabaceae,* the pea family','','Leaves: Early spring<br />Flowers: They\'re at their peak in late spring, although you can still find a few good ones in the summer and fall.','Sunny places, meadows, pastures, open fields, roadsides, lawns, parks, disturbed habitats','Throughout most of North America','Look for a small plant with leaflets of 3s and a small white flower head consisting of many tiny, tubular, 2-sided flowers.','This low, Eurasian, spreading, herbaceous plant, 4 to 16 inches tall, creeps along the ground and roots at nodes. It bears a rounded, white flower head and 3-parted palmate-compound leaves that are familiar to anyone who\'s ever ventured outdoors.<br /><br />The leaves come up on a separate stalk from the flower head. Oval to elliptical, the leaflets grow to about 0.5 to 1.25 inches in length, with a seam down their length, a *V*-shaped chevron marking each leaflet, and a tiny notch at the leaflet\'s tip.<br /><br />20 to 40 tiny, long, narrow, bilaterally symmetrical flowers crowd onto the flower head, which grows above a long, slender, unbranched, leafless flower stalk.<br />The root system is fibrous.<br />','Pick the young leaves and the flower heads by hand. If you\'re using the flowers for tea, including a few mature leaves won\'t do any harm<br /><br />The best time to collect the flowers is when the greatest number of plants have come into full flower at the same time, and most of the flowers are brightly colored, usually in late spring. Collect only the most attractive-looking flower heads. These are the best. Avoid those that still include some immature, green flowers, and those with brown, withered flowers, which taste terrible.','You can add a few of the youngest leaves, raw, to salads, but they\'re hard to digest. It\'s much better to cook them like other greens, for about 15 minutes. They\'re not one of my favorite vegetables, with a raw string bean/turnip flavor, but some people like them.<br /><br />People have used an infusion of the flower heads since prehistoric times. Use only the whitest flower heads, which are the best quality.<br /><br />You can also pull the flowers off the flower heads with your fingers and add them raw, to salads (the flowers, not your fingers!) Or cook the flowers in virtually any dish that calls for vegetables. They cook in about 10 to 15 minutes. Although somewhat fibrous, they taste like sweet snap peas. I also like showering them, raw, onto ice cream, where they make attractive, sweet sprinkles.<br /><br />You can also dehydrate them, grind them into a powder in a blender in a blender, and use them to supplement the protein of whole grains in breads and muffins. This works for the completely brown, dry flower heads, which contain the seeds, too, although they\'re not as tasty as the flowers. Add the meal of the flowers, or the dried flower heads and seeds, to whole-grain flour to use in breads, pancakes, and muffins.','•Small herbaceous plant with alternate, 3-parted, palmate-compound leaves growing on a slender stem separate from the flower\'s stem<br />•Roundish, white flower head packed with many long, narrow flowers<br />•Oval to elliptical leaflets with a midrib running down the their length, creating a seam<br />•A *V*-shaped chevron on each leaflet<br />•A tiny notch at the tip of each leaflet',NULL,'Red clover *(T. pratense)*, also edible, resembles white clover, but it\'s larger, the flowers and leaves arise the same flower stalks, and the flowers are magenta, not white.<br /><br />People confuse wood sorrel *(Oxalis spp.)* with clover, but this edible plant has heart-shaped leaves and completely different flowers.','No information is available.','Various Native American tribes used an infusion of the flowers for fevers, coughs, and colds, although I\'m skeptical about it\'s efficacy. An infusion of the flowers has even been used as an eyewash.<br /><br />','','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(27,193,'Sheep Sorrel','*Rumex acetosella*','Family: *Polygonaceae,* the knotweed or smartweed family','','Early spring to late fall—best in early spring and fall','Sunny lawns, fields, openings in the woods, trail sides, open fields, parks, roadsides, disturbed habitats, and acidic soil','Throughout most of the US and Canada','Look for basal rosettes of arrow-shaped long-stalked leaves in early spring and fall, and racemes of the reddish-tinged, branching, flowering stems in the summer.','This unique plant has leaves that resemble a sheep’s face—there’s a pointed *nose* at the tip, and 2 spreading *ears* (lobes) perpendicular to the arrow-shaped leaf’s broad base, although the very youngest leaves are oval. A papery sheath wraps around the stem adjacent to the leaf axils.<br /><br />Spreading by rhizomes, this hairless European perennial, which also has a taproot, begins as a basal rosette with long-stalked leaves 1.5 to 3 inches long in early spring, and new rosettes develop in the fall.<br /><br />A slender, branched, deeply ridged, jointed stem 1.5 to 9 (sometimes up to 18) inches tall in mid-spring, with much smaller, alternate, stalkless leaves that may be arrow-shaped or linear, grows in mid-spring. Long, lacy, loosely branched racemes of tiny, yellow-green male flowers, plus tiny reddish female flowers, bloom on the upper stalks in late spring and early summer. Tiny, inconspicuous, reddish to yellow-brown fruits in papery wrappers ripen in the summer.','The basal leaves are best. Grab a bunch with 1 hand, hold down the leaf stalks with the other, and break off the leaves. You can also strip the leaves off the flower stalks with your fingers.','Sheep sorrel basal leaves have an intensely lemony flavor, much better than commercial garden sorrel *(R. acetosa).* People who try it say: \"Not b...a...a..a...d!\" It\'s so tasty, I eat it at every opportunity, even though I\'m a vegan! The leaves on the stem aren\'t as good, and the flowers are unpleasantly bitter and astringent.<br /><br />Use the leaves raw in salads and sandwiches. They\'re excellent in soups and stews, cooked about 10 minutes, but you can use it in any dish that calls for leafy vegetables. You can even bake them into bread, where their strong flavor won\'t get lost.','•Long-stalked arrow-shaped basal leaves in early spring and fall<br />•Very young basal leaves oval<br />•Branching stalk in mid-spring and summer with racemes of reddish flowers<br />•Leaves strongly lemon-flavored',NULL,'Bindweed *(Convolvulus spp.)* also has arrow-shaped leaves, but it\'s a vine, not an upright plant, and its flowers look like its relative, morning glory *(Ipomoea purpurea.)*<br /><br />Wood sorrel *(Rumex spp.)* also protects itself from non-human herbivores with a lemony flavor, but this unrelated edible has nothing else in common with sheep sorrel other than its flavor and name.','Sheep sorrel provides vitamins C, A, B-complex, D, E, K, P and U, plus the minerals calcium, phosphorus, magnesium, potassium,  silicon, iron, sulfur, copper, iodine, manganese, and zinc.','Sheep sorrel contains tartaric acid and the anthraquinones chrysophanol, emodin, and rhein, glycosides such as hyperoside, and the quercitin-3d-galactoside.<br /><br />Because of its vitamin C, it has been used successfully for scurvy. It has also been used as a diuretic, for inflammation, cancer, diarrhea, scurvy, worms, intestinal parasites, and fever. With all its biologically active constituents, it certainly deserves scientific investigation.','Don\'t believe the inaccurate scare-literature that says sheep sorrel is dangerous because it contains oxalic acid. Unless you have kidney stones, it\'s no more hazardous than spinach, and people have been enjoying it in good health for thousands of years (maybe if I keep eating it, I\'ll get to enjoy it in good health for thousands of years too!)','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(28,199,'Shepherd\'s Purse','*Capsella bursa-pastoris*','Family: *Brassicaceae* or *Cruciferae,* the mustard or cabbage family','','1. Basal leaves: Early spring and late mid- to late fall<br /><br />2. Flower buds and flowers: Mid-spring','One of the first plants to colonize newly disturbed habitats, it grows in full sunlight or partial shade, along roadsides, and in fields, pastures, lawns, and parks.','Throughout most of the North America','Look for basal rosettes of blunt-lobed or toothed, lance-shaped leaves, with lobes facing outward, in early spring. In mid-spring, look for the addition of long, slender stalks with loosely configurted heart-shaped or triangular seed pods, plus tiny, 4-petaled white flowers on top.','Here\'s a European annual with a basal rosette of lobed to toothed leaves, plus heart-shaped to triangular seed pods that resemble purses shepherds used in ancient times.<br /><br />Shepherd’s purse begins with a basal rosette of stalked, lobed to deeply toothed, lance-shaped leaves up to 9 inches long, broader toward the tip, arising from a slender, white taproot. Unlike similar-looking rosettes, the leaves\' lobes point outward, and there\'s no white, milky sap.<br /><br />In mid-spring, long, slender, erect flower stalks, branching from the base, grow from 8 inches to 2.5 feet tall. Smaller, alternate, stalkless, lance-shaped or linear leaves, sometimes with tiny teeth, clasp the stems with 2 small, pointed lobes at their bases.<br /><br />The tiny, stalked flowers, growing inside 4 green, oval sepals, have 4 white petals which form a cross. They grow on loose terminal racemes. Maturing from the bottom up, the flowers metamorphosize into long-stalked, flattened, heart-shaped to triangular, 2-parted seed pods 0.25 inch long. The mature seeds inside are very tiny.','Sever the young rosette from the root with a pocket knife in early spring or fall, shake off the soil and debris, and bag. I find this the most mild-tasting of all the mustards, good in salads, sandwiches, or cooked dishes that call for vegetables. They cook in 10 to 15 minutes. Include stronger-tasting ingredients, herbs, or spices, or your dish will taste too bland. The basal leaves become tough after the stem appears, so get them very early in the spring, or in the fall when they often reappear.<br /><br />In season in mid-spring, the flowers, flower buds, and the top part of the stem that\'s tender enough to pinch off, taste like broccoli, excellent in salads (cooking would probably drown out the flavor), but small enough that it\'s hardly worth my while to harvest. Kids invariably love collecting and eating these parts, and rarely leave any unpicked, even if they hate broccoli!<br /><br />The seedpods are delicious—spicy and flavorful—but only in foraging books by botanists who recopy 3rd hand info and don\'t forage or cook themselves. In reality, they\'re as tasteless as my jokes, definitely not worth collecting!<br /><br />Although the root is technically edible, it\'s too small and hairy to be worthwhile, and the seeds are barely visible.','The basal leaves of early spring and fall are the most mild-flavored of the mustard greens. While you can certainly grab handfuls of leaves, cutting the root just under the center of the rosette with a pocketknife gets you the entire rosette in a second, and while it\'s still intact, you can shake off most of the debris before bagging the plant. Use the leaves raw in salads or sandwiches, or cook 10 to 15 minutes along with more flavorful ingredients in any dish that calls for cooked vegetables.<br /><br />The flowers and tender tops of the stems taste like broccoli—great in salads but too small for cooked dishes, where their flavor would get lost. In fact, I rarely bother with the work it would take to collect them in quantity. Nevertheless, kids on my tours adore them, and rarely leave any unpicked.<br /><br />The seed pods, on the other hand, are spicy and delicious, but only in foraging books that I didn\'t write! Once inside your mouth, they\'re as tasteless as my jokes, and definitely not worth picking.<br /><br />The small, hairy root, albeit edible, also isn\'t worth the trouble to harvest and clean, much less chew!','•Basal rosette of lance-shaped, blunt-lobed or deeply toothed leaves<br />•Lobes pointing laterally<br />•Lobes larger toward the leaf\'s tip<br />•Slender stems up to 2.5 feet high, branching at the base<br />•Clusters of tiny, 4-petaled, white flowers at the top of the stems<br />•Loose racemes of small, heart-shaped to triangular seed pods<br />•Small, white, hairy taproot',NULL,'The common dandelion *(Taraxacum officinale),* wild lettuce *(Lactuca species),* and chicory *(Cichorum intybus),* all edible, have similar basal leaves, but the first 2 don\'t have lobes that point outward consistently, all 3 have white, milky sap, which shepherd\'s purse lacks, and the flowers and seeds are all very different from shepherd\'s purse\'s. Furthermore, chicory leaves usually have some red discoloration, plus some hairs on the underside of the leaf\'s midrib.<br /><br />Poor man\'s pepper *(Lepidium virginicum)* and its relatives *(Lepidium spp.),* all edible, have basal leaves with no colored sap too, but their leaves are aren\'t lobed and blunt. The seeds are never heart-shaped or triangular, and poor man\'s pepper\'s teeth point toward the leaf\'s base.','Shepherd\'s purse leaves provide vitamins A, C, K, B1, B2, B3, choline, and inositol, plus the minerals include calcium, potassium, and phosphorus. They also contain fumaric acid, which may inhibit cancer, especially if you\'re a lab mouse!','An infusion of the whole plant, except the roots, contains saponins, choline, acetylcholine, and tyramine. It\'s supposed to be astringent, anti-inflammatory, hemostatic, and diuretic, but when I tried it on a paper cut, it had no effect on the bleeding, and didn\'t make me run to the bathroom either!<br /><br />Used during or after childbirth and to ease difficult menstruation, it\'s also supposed to constrict the blood vessels, lower blood pressure, and contract the uterus, but I haven\'t seen any science either verifying or disproving these claims.','1. Because of its possible effects on the blood, this plant is contraindicated for pregnant women.<br /><br />2. Stay away from the tiny, sticky seeds if you\'re a microscopic invertebrate. You\'ll get stuck to them, and be absorbed by the carnivorous plant embryo!','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(29,210,'Common Blue Violet','*Viola sororia sororia, V. papilionacea*','*Violaceae,* the violet family','','The leaves are edible from early- through mid-spring, before they get tough and coarse in late spring, although sometimes new tender leaves come up where the older ones were mowed.<br /><br />The edible flowers bloom in mid-spring.','Gardems, lawns, meadows, fields, parks, damp woodland openings, trail edges, near riverbanks, and along roadsides','Eastern and much of central North America','Look for dense stands of odorless, heart-shaped, shallow-toothed leaves, each arising from the ground on its own leaf stalk. In mid-spring, look for the addition of bilaterally symmetrical, medium-sized violet flowers with 5 petals—the 3 lower ones deeply veined, and the side ones bearded deep inside the flower.','This common, widespread native colonial plant’s only leaves are basal. Odorless, heart-shaped, hairless, shallow-toothed, they grow 3 to 5 inches long and 3 to 5 inches across. Tightly curled at first, each leaf grows on top of a single, slender stalk 3 to 8 inches high.<br /><br />Barely taller than the leaves, each bilaterally symmetrical, scentless, violet-colored flower also arises from the ground on its own slender flower stalk. Of the 5 rounded petals, the 2 side ones are bearded with bushy stamens near the flower\'s throat. All the 3 lower ones are deeply veined, and the lowest is slightly spurred. Hundreds of these colorful colonial flowers, 0.75 to 1 inch across, fill meadows in mid-spring, coming from the branched rhizomes about 0.5 inches thick.<br /><br />The showy springtime flowers are sterile, but in the fall, the fertile flowers—inconspicuous oblong, beige capsules about 0.5 inch long, hide at ground level. They self-fertilize, mature, and split lengthwise into 3 parts to release a few dozen tiny, spherical seeds that look like ant eggs, translucent white at first, then dark brown when mature.<br /><br /><br />','In early- and mid-spring, hold down handfuls of plants with one hand, and pull off as many leaves and violet flowers as possible, with as little of the tougher flower- and leaf stalks as possible. Other parts of the plant are not edible.','Violets have a mild, subtle, but quite enjoyable flavor—somewhat bland at first, but with a surprise bite as part of the aftertaste. They\'re excellent raw, in salads and sandwiches, and they\'re great as cooked greens, steamed and served with olive oil, salt, and pepper, or in any vegetable dish that calls for cooked greens. They make an excellent replacement for spinach, for example. They cook in about 10 minutes.','• Heart-shaped, shallow-toothed leaves 3 to 5 inches across<br />• Each leaf arising from the ground on its own leaf stalk<br />•Bilaterally symmetrical, medium-sized 5-petaled, violet flowers<br />• Each flower arising from the ground on its own flower stalk<br />•Prominent veins on the 3 lower petals<br />•Side petals bearded deep inside the flower<br />•Small spur at the base of the lower petal<br />•No fragrance','Avoid violet species with yellow flowers, which may cause nausea and vomiting.<br /><br />Don’t confuse the common blue violet with the poisonous larkspur *(Delphinium tricorne),* with a large, erect spur behind its violet colored, 5-petaled flower, and leaves different from the violet\'s.<br /><br />The poisonous monk’s hood *(Aconitum uncinatum)* also has a violet flower, has different leaves. Also, an upper sepal covers 2 of its petals like a helmet.<br /><br />Don’t eat the African violet *(Saintpaulia spp.)*, a non-wild house plant that’s not a violet at all.','There are close to 80 similar edible violet-colored violet species in the US, and even the common blue violet is now considered a subspecies of a highly variable species that includes, among others, a subspecies with a white flower *(V. sororia albiflora)*, and a very common hybrid of that subspecies with the violet that results in a blue-and-white flower. My preference is to enjoy these violets and let the botanists who are paid to do so work out the differences!','The leaves provide vitamin A and C, the flowers vitamin C.','Not a major medicinal plant, a poultice of the leaves has been applied externally to relieve headaches and for boils, and an infusion of the leaves and flowers has been used for dysentery, coughs and colds, although I\'m very skeptical about any of these uses actually working.','Eat only the young leaves and flowers in the spring. Don\'t eat the rhizomes, which may cause nausea and vomiting, or the inconspicuous ground level fall flower, fruit, or seeds.','','','','',NULL,0,'1','',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(31,222,'test','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,234,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(30,221,'Wild Carrot','*Daucus carota*','*Apiaceae* or *Umbelliferae,* the umbellifers','','Taproot: Fall, winter (in warm regions), and early spring<br />Seeds: Mid-summer through fall',NULL,NULL,NULL,'People are surprised to learn that the wild carrot is the same plant as Queen Anne\'s Lace, a well-known wildflower.<br /><br />This European biennial’s first-year form consists of a basal rosette made from lacy, branching, finely divided feather-compound with hairy leaf stalks and a whitish, carrot-scented taproot 2 to 8 inches long, usually with many side branches, all appearing very early in the spring.<br /><br />The basal rosette returns in early spring the second year, then develops a hairy flower stalk 2 to 3 feet tall in mid-spring. This is topped by flat-topped clusters of tiny white flowers only 0.125 inches across—the Queen Anne’s lace people recognize—often with a tiny, dark purple flower in the center. Stiff, three-forked bracts grow under the flower clusters.<br />',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(32,223,'','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(33,224,'','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(34,225,'','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(35,226,'','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(36,227,'','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(37,228,'','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(38,232,'','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(39,233,'','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,'1','1',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(40,234,'','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','',NULL,0,'0','0',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
