INSERT INTO `content_smalls` VALUES (1,1,'Plants','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(2,3,'Amaranth Porridge','Here is an update version of the classic Scottish breakfast dish with the addition of berries that will make the 3 Bears so happy, they\'ll be willing to share their cereal with Goldilocks! Serve hot.	<br /><br />2 tbs. grape seed oil or canola oil<br />1 cup steel-cut oats<br />1/4 cup amaranth<br />1/4 cup lecithin granules<br />4 cups soy-rice milk, nut milk, or other vegan milk<br />2 tsp. clear liquid stevia (an herbal sweetener available in health food stores)<br />1 tsp. cinnamon, ground<br /><br />1 tsp. vanilla extract<br />1/4 tsp. orange extract<br />1/4 tsp. almond extract<br />1/4 tsp. salt<br />1 large green apple, chopped<br />1-1/2 cups red mulberries or other berries<br />2/3 cup raisins<br />1/4 cup lecithin granules (available in health food stores‚ (optional)<br />1/4 cup oat bran (optional)	<br /><br />1. In a saucepan, cook the oats and amaranth in the oil over medium heat 5 minutes, or until fragrant, stirring often.<br /><br />2. Add all ingredients except the lecithin and bran, bring to a boil over medium heat, stirring constantly, reduce the heat to low and simmer, uncovered, 30 minutes, or until the porridge is thickened and soft, stirring occasionally.<br /><br />3. Remove from the heat and let set, uncovered, 15 minutes.<br /><br />Serves 6<br /><br />Preparation time: 15 minutes<br /><br />Cooking and setting time: 45 minutes<br />','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(3,5,'Amaranth Seeds','You can blow away most of amaranth\'s chaff and get large quantities of these tasty, nutritious, tiny, black, circular seeds.','','',NULL,NULL,30,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(4,6,'Mature Common Amaranth','Note the tall spikes, densely covered with flowers or seeds, and the oval, smooth-edged, alternate, long-stalked leaves.','','',NULL,NULL,60,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(5,7,' Mature Low Amaranth','Note the irregular, alternate, elliptical, long-stalked, smooth-edged, notched leaves, and the spikes of tiny seeds. Here it creeps along the ground, but it can also be upright.','','',NULL,NULL,29,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(6,10,'Savory Chicory with Sweet Red Dal','Here’s a quick, delicious way to prepare these healthful tiny red lentils, where savory chicory with creamy pignola nuts and sweet spices make the dish special.<br />	<br />2 tbs. corn oil<br />2 cups very young chicory leaves, chopped<br />1 tsp. cardmom<br />1/2 tsp. cloves, ground<br />1/2 tsp. cinnamon, ground<br />3 cups soy milk, oat milk, or nut milk<br />1 cup red dal<br />1/2 cup currants<br />1/4 cup pignola nuts<br />1 tsp. fresh orange rind<br />1 tsp. salt	<br /><br />1. Sauté the chicory in the corn oil with the cardamom, cloves, and cinnamon 10 minutes.<br /><br />2. Transfer to a saucepan with all the remaining ingredients except the salt 35 minutes, bring to a boil over medium heat, reduce the heat to low, cover, and simmer 35 minutes or until the lentils are tender.<br /><br />3. Stir in the salt at the end to prevent the beans from staying hard.	<br /><br />Serves 4 to 6<br /><br />Preparation time: 45 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(7,11,'Chicory Young Basal Rosette and Taproot','These young, toothed leaves, before the lobes develop and they become bitter, are the best to eat. Note the very long taproot, and the remnant of last year\'s flower stalk—good field characteristics for identifying the young plant.','','',NULL,NULL,31,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(8,12,'Chicory Young Basal Rosette','The basal rosette with toothed leaves, where  the underside of the midrib of one of the center leaves is tinged with red, plus the woody remnant of last year\'s flower stalk, characterize chicory in early spring. This stage, before the leaves develop lobes, is when you want to cut off the top of the roots and collect the rosettes.','','',NULL,NULL,32,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(9,13,'Chicory Stand in Flower','The nearly leafless flower stalks with short, zigzag branches, and the showy, blue, composite flowers, bloom along roadsides and disturbed soil throughout the country.','','',NULL,NULL,169,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(10,14,'Chicory Flower','Chicory\'s blue composite flowers consist of many petal-like ray flowers, each fringed with 5 jagged points at the tips. The many stamens look like upside-down scissors tucked into a sheath.','','',NULL,NULL,33,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(11,16,'Garlic Spread','Here’s a savory French garlic butter-style spread based on miso, lecithin, and olive oil instead of butter that will flavor bread (it\'s especially good on bread you\'re going to toast), pasta, vegetables, soups, or anywhere else you use seasoned butter. With the addition of a small amount of olive oil, it\'s also great for sautéing.	<br /><br />3 tbs. wild garlic or 6 cloves of commercial garlic<br /><br />2/3 fresh parsley<br /><br />1 cup mellow miso (available in health food stores)<br /><br />1/2 cup olive oil<br /><br />1/4 cup lecithin granules (available in health food stores)<br /><br />2 tsp. rosemary, ground<br /><br />1 tsp. marjoram, ground<br /><br />1 tsp. sage, ground<br /><br />1/2 tsp. chili paste or hot sauce<br /><br />1/4 tsp. turmeric	<br /><br /><br />1. Chop the garlic and parsley in a food processor.<br /><br /><br />2. Add the remaining ingredients and purée.	<br /><br /><br />Makes 1-3/4 cups<br /><br />Preparation time: 5 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(12,17,'Baked Burdock Root','Here’s an irresistible wild snack food you’ll nibble on until the last bit is gone!<br /><br />4 cups burdock root, thinly sliced<br /><br />1/2 cup Vegan Garlic Butter (see above)<br /><br />1/2 tsp. Vege-sal (a seasoned salt available in health food stores)<br /><br />2 tbs. water<br /><br />1/2 tsp. lemon juice	<br /><br /><br />Mix all ingredients together and bake, covered, in an oiled casserole dish, 45 minutes, or until the water has evaporated and the roots are lightly browned.<br /><br />Preparation time: 5 minutes<br /><br />Baking time: 45 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(13,18,'Burdock Basal Rosette and Taproot','Burdock\'s taproot has lots of branches. They usually don\'t all come up when you dig up the main taproot, and what\'s left behind will subsequently regenerate new plants.','','',NULL,NULL,34,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(14,19,'Burdock Basal Rosette and Taproot','The large, coarse, long-stalked, wedge-shaped leaves, with their white undersides, reveal the whereabouts of the large, deep taproot, which is white after being scrubbed.','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(15,20,'Burdock Flower Stalk','This is the stage where the immature central flower stalk is delicious peeled, parboiled, and prepared like artichoke hearts.','','',NULL,NULL,35,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(16,21,'Burdock Flower','The spherical composite flower consists of many tiny flowers bunched together like a purple shaving brush, set above a round, green, prickly base.','','',NULL,NULL,36,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(17,22,'Burdock Burrs','These annoying burrs, which stick to clothing or pets, are full of seeds, accounting for how the Eurasian plant got to America and spread across the country.','','',NULL,NULL,37,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(18,23,'Burdock Seeds','The small, hard, brown, curved seeds are only good to throw on your neighbor\'s garden. Next year, you can help him or her get rid of the \"weeds,\" which you get to eat!','','',NULL,NULL,38,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(19,25,'Garlicky Chickweed with Penne','Here’s a fast and tasty recipe where chickweed’s robust flavor holds its own with the garlic. Along with the other seasonings, these 2 primary flavors add a savory element to the more mild-flavored pasta.	<br /><br />3 cups penne pasta<br /><br />2 cloves of garlic, chopped<br /><br />8 cups chickweed, chopped<br /><br />2 tbs. corn oil<br /><br />1/2 tsp. marjoram, ground<br /><br />1/2 tsp. black pepper, ground<br /><br />1 tbs. tamari soy sauce (available in health food stores) or soy sauce, or to taste	<br /><br />1. Cook the penne in boiling, salted water with a dash of olive oil according to the manufacturer’s directions.<br /><br />2. Meanwhile, sauté the garlic in the corn oil 5 minutes, or until very lightly browned. Take care not to burn the garlic, which is very easy to do, and would ruin the dish.<br /><br />3. Stir in the pasta and other remaining ingredients, reduce the heat to low, cover, and cook 5 minutes, or until the chickweed is just wilted.<br /><br />Serves 4 to 6<br /><br />Preparation time: 20 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(20,26,'Star Chickweed','The stalkless opposite leaves, tiny, white, split petals, and stalked seed pods, plus the slender stem, characterize this plant.','','',NULL,NULL,39,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(21,27,'Common Chickweed','The opposite, smooth-edges, stalked, spade-shaped leaves, and the row of white hairs along the stem, make this species easy to ID, even without flowers.','','',NULL,NULL,40,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(22,28,'Star Chickweed Flowers','The 5 white petals of these alphabetic flowers, set inside 5 green sepals, are split so deeply, each looks like the letter \"V,\" while the single pistil spreads out into a letter \"Y,\" to catch the pollen made on the tiny, pink-tipped stamens. ','','',NULL,NULL,41,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(23,29,'Mouse-ear Chickweed','With opposite leaves and 5 deeply split petals, this species is similar to star and common chickweed, except that it\'s hairy all over.','','',NULL,NULL,42,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(24,30,'Spotted Spurge','The dark marks on the leaves, lack of a row of hair on the stem, and white, milky sap, readily differentiate this superficially similar poisonous plant from chickweed, as long as you pay attention.','','',NULL,NULL,43,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(25,31,'Scarlet Pimpernel','This poisonous plant looks like chickweed, but it lacks chickweed\'s row of tiny hairs on the stem, and it\'s flower is scarlet, not red. This plant is especially toxic to the French: They seek him here, they seek him there, Those Frenchies seek him everywhere. Is he in heaven or is he in hell? That demned elusive Pimpernel. He meddles with the Frenchie Revolution, Popping in and out each week, Spoiling every lovely execution, La, what cheek! They seek him here, they seek him there, Those Frenchies seek him everywhere. If you should see him, please do give a yell! That demned elusive Pimpernel. They seek him here, they seek him there, Those Frenchies seek him everywhere. Oh, Pimpy, how the Frenchies do implore you, Simply to stay home in bed. With all your interference, It\'s a chore to chop a head! They seek him here, they seek him there, The ladies seek him everywhere! He give the Frenchies nothing but frustration. Sink me! He\'s a spoilsport. Each and every demned decapitation, He cuts short. They seek him here, they seek him there, Those Frenchies seek him everywhere. Is he in heaven or is he in hell? That demned elusive Pimpernel. ','','',NULL,NULL,44,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(26,34,'Common Plantain Basal Rosette and Root System','All the oval, ribbed leaves arise from the fibrous roots.','','',NULL,NULL,45,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(27,35,'Common Plantain Young Basal Rosette','If you\'re going to eat common plantain\'s leaves, this is the stage where they\'re at their most edible, before they become fully grown and too tough.','','',NULL,NULL,46,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(28,36,'Common Plantain in Flower','At this stage, the leaves taste like shoes. You can cook them, and they\'ll taste like cooked shoes!','','',NULL,NULL,47,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(29,37,'Common Plantain Flowers','Easy to overlook, the green flower spikes are covered with protruding stamens.','','',NULL,NULL,48,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(30,38,'Long-leaf Plantain in Flower, and Basal Rosette','The basal rosette of narrow, ribbed leaves makes this plant distinct whether or not it has its inconspicuous flowers.','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(31,39,'Long-leaf Plantain Basal Rosette','If you\'re going to try eating these tough leaves, do so now, while they\'re still young, and less tough than they will be later on!','','',NULL,NULL,49,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(32,40,'Long-leaf Plantain in Flower','The small, cylindrical flowers atop the slender, leafless flower stalk, and the protruding, white stamens make it easy to recognize this common plant.','','',NULL,NULL,50,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(33,41,'Long-leaf Plantain Flower','The small, brown base, green, pineapple-shaped top, and protruding, white stamens, all growing on a slender flower stalk, make this flower distinct.','','',NULL,NULL,51,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(34,43,'Immature Asiatic Dayflower Stand','These plants, with smooth-edged, alternate, pointed, grass-like, stalkless leaves, grow in dense stands.','','',NULL,NULL,52,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(35,44,'Asiatic Dayflower Flower and Seeds','The 2 bright blue petals hide the inconspicuous transparent white one underneath. The pointed, smooth-edged, alternate, grass-like leaves\' bases wrap around the stem. The small, pea-like seeds grow in pairs.','','',NULL,NULL,53,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(36,45,'Asiatic Dayflower Flower','The 2 larger sky-blue petals overshadow the pale white one underneath, leading Linneaus to name the genus Commelina, after a family with 3 brothers. 2 were famous botanists. The 3rd was a ne\'er-do-well: His business failed, he went into debt, the woman he loved married someone else, and he died young (outside of that, he had a great life)!  The 3 brown stamens at the bottom produce pollen, but the 3 brown-centered yellow ones on top lost that function. They\'re sterile, but they help attract insects. ','','',NULL,NULL,54,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(37,46,'Asiatic Dayflower Seeds','The paired, ellipsoid, yellow-green seeds rest in the elliptical fused sepals.','','',NULL,NULL,55,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(38,47,'Spiderwort','Much larger that the Asiatic dayflower, this edible plant\'s long, floppy leaves look a little like spiders\' legs (wort is an old word for plant). Also, the flower has 3 large, blue petals, not 2.','','',NULL,NULL,56,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(39,49,'Mature Common Mallow','Common mallow\'s long-stalked, roundish, pleated leaves, small 5-petaled flowers, and fruits resembling wheels of cheese make it easy to recognize.','','',NULL,NULL,57,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(40,50,'Common Mallow in Fruit','The small, 5-petaled flowers\' bushy mixture of stamens and pistil, plus the pink-lined petals, make them quite distinct.','','',NULL,NULL,58,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(41,51,'Common Mallow Flowers','The small, 5-petaled flowers\' bushy mixture of stamens and pistil in the center, plus the pink-lined petals, make them quite distinct.','','',NULL,NULL,59,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(42,52,'Low Amaranth with Seed Spikes','This species has uncharacteristically sparse seed spikes, but the leaves make a superb potherb. Here it\'s upright, but it can also creep along the ground.','','',NULL,NULL,61,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(43,53,'Common Amaranth Seed Heads','The hundreds of tiny, bristly looking bracts (modified leaves) on these upright spikes hold thousands of delicious seeds.','','',NULL,NULL,62,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(44,55,'test','wolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdfwolly natureas dfasd fasd asd fasdf asdf','','',NULL,NULL,63,0,'0','',0,'D'),(45,56,'test','','','',NULL,NULL,64,0,NULL,'',0,'D'),(46,57,'asdf','','','',NULL,NULL,65,0,NULL,'',0,'D'),(47,58,'test3','','','',NULL,NULL,66,0,NULL,'',0,'D'),(48,59,'asdfasd','','','',NULL,NULL,67,0,NULL,'',0,'D'),(49,60,'Curly Dock Leaf and Seed Spikes','The narrow leaf with its wavy margins, and the branching spikes of tiny seeds, make this plant distinct.','','',NULL,NULL,68,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(50,61,'Curly Dock Basal Rosette and Taproot','The stout taproot, yellow where cut or scraped, and the large, narrow leaves with very wavy margins characterize the young plant.','','',NULL,NULL,69,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(51,62,'Curly Dock Immature and Mature','The immature plant, with its basal rosette of long, narrow, wavy-margined, smooth-edged leaves, as well as the mature plant, with similar, smaller, alternate leaves, and dense clusters of flowers and tiny seeds on upright spikes, both have the same yellow taproot.','','',NULL,NULL,70,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(52,63,'Curly Dock Flowers','These tiny green flowers depend on wild for pollination, so inefficient that there are very many of them. Because no insects are involved in pollination, they can afford to be small and inconspicuous.','','',NULL,NULL,71,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(53,64,'Curly Dock Seeds','These tiny, reddish-brown seeds, growing in the hundreds on branching spikes, hide inside so much inedible material that there\'s no way to turn them into a meal.','','',NULL,NULL,72,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(54,65,'Bitter or Broadleaf Dock, Basal Rosette','This awful-tasting plant looks a little like its relative, curly dock, but the leaves are broader, the edges aren\'t very wavy, and the leaves midribs are reddish.','','',NULL,NULL,73,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(55,67,'kjhk','','','',NULL,NULL,74,0,NULL,'',0,'D'),(56,68,'Vegan Herb Butter','Vegan Herb Butter	<br /><br />Here’s a savory French garlic butter-style spread based on miso, lecithin, and olive oil that will flavor bread (it\'s especially good spread on bread you\'re going to toast), pasta, vegetables, soups, or anywhere else you use butter. With the addition of a small amount of olive oil, it\'s also great for sautéing.	<br /><br />3 tbs. wild garlic or 6 cloves of commercial garlic<br />2/3 cups fresh parsley<br />1 cup mellow miso<br />1/2 cup olive oil<br />1/4 cup lecithin granules<br />2 tsp. rosemary, ground<br />1 tsp. marjoram, ground<br />1 tsp. sage, ground<br />1/2 tsp. chili paste (available in Asian groceries)<br />1/4 tsp. turmeric	<br /><br />1. Chop the garlic and goutweed, waterleaf or parsley in a food processor.<br /><br />2. Add the remaining ingredients and purée.	<br /><br />Makes 1-3/4 cups<br /><br />Preperation time: 5 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(57,69,'Stalking the Wild Curly Dock','Here’s a wonderful lemony-flavored dish you can serve as a side dish or as an appetizer, based on seasoned, baked curly dock flower stalks and leaf stalks.	<br /><br />2-2/3 cups young curly dock flower stalks or leaf midribs, chopped<br />2 tbs. Wild Herb Butter<br />1/2 tsp. salt	<br /><br />Combine all ingredients in an oiled baking dish and bake, covered, in a preheated 350 degree oven 25 minutes.	<br /><br />Serves 4 to 6<br /><br />Preparation time:<br /><br />Baking time: 30 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(58,70,'Dandelion Leaf, Taproot, Flower and Seeds','The familiar spherical, white seed head points its parachutes outward and holds its seeds in the center, along with some sepals held over from the flower. The flower- and seed stalk is leafless, hairless, and hollow.<br />The yellow composite flower, with green sepals below, consists of many individual ray flowers.<br />The stiff, light brown taproot usually includes branches.<br />The leaf\'s teeth always point toward the leaf base.<br />Each tiny white parachute flies off with 1 tiny, brown seed.','','',NULL,NULL,75,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(59,71,'Young Dandelion Basal Rosette','This is when you want to collect dandelion leaves, while they\'re still young, well before the flowers appear. And comparatively broad-leaved varieties, such as this one, taste the best.','','',NULL,NULL,76,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(60,72,'Dandelion Flower','What look like petals are actually individual flowers, called ray flowers, bunched together to form a composite flower head, allowing 1 insect to pollinate many flowers at once, and helping dandelions become as common as they are. The sepals, modified leaves that enclosed the flower when it was a bud, remain at the flower\'s base, bent backward or relflexed. They\'re bitter. Remove them before eating the flower.','','',NULL,NULL,77,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(61,73,'Dandelion Seed Head','The spherical, white seed head, with tiny, brown seeds resembling sunflower seeds in the center, isn\'t edible, but you can blow away the seeds and make a wish. And your wish will always come true, so long as you wish for more dandelions!','','',NULL,NULL,78,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(62,74,'Dandelion in Flower','','','',NULL,NULL,79,0,'1','',0,NULL),(63,75,'Chicory Basal Rosette','Also edible, chicory\'s basal leaves resemble dandelions, but the teeth are usually smaller, and they don\'t all point toward the leaf\'s base. As a perennial with a tall flower stalk, most of the rosettes maintain the skeleton of the previous year\'s whitish, woody flower stalk into the spring, as seen here.','','',NULL,NULL,80,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(64,76,'Wild Lettuce Basal Rosette','Also edible, wild lettuce\'s basal leaves resemble dandelions\' but the more shallow teeth don\'t all point toward the leaf base, they\'re usually at least somewhat hairy, and there are fibrous roots instead of a taproot underground.','','',NULL,NULL,81,0,'0','',0,NULL),(65,77,'Dandelions Thai Style','Dandelions Thai Style	<br /><br />Simmering dandelion leaves after sautéeing them removes their bitterness and makes them delicious, even more so with traditional Thai ingredients.	Serve over Asian clear noodles.<br /><br />1/4 cup coconut oil<br />9 cups young common dandelion leaves or other wild vegetables<br />1 cloves of garlic, chopped<br />1-1/2 cups coconut milk<br />1-1/2 cups soft tofu, drained and diced1 tbs. kudzu or arrowroot<br />1-1/2 tbs. lime juice<br />2 tbs. basil<br />1 tsp. powdered ginger<br />1 tsp. cloves, ground<br />1-1/2 tsp. salt, or to taste<br />tsp. hot sauce, or to taste	<br /><br />1. Saute the common dandelion leaves, tofu, and garlic in the oil 10 minutes.<br /><br />2. Meanwhile, puree the remaining ingredients in a blender.<br /><br />3. Add the puree to the dandelions, bring to a boil, over medium heat, stirring constantly, reduce the heat to low, cover, and simmer 10 minutes.	<br /><br />Serves 4	<br /><br />Preparation/cooking time: 30 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(66,79,'Daylily Ice Cream','Here’s a wonderfully flavored wild ice cream. You can create an even more exotic dessert by stuffing additional fresh day-lily flowers with it, and sealing them with toothpicks!	<br /><br />2  cups soy, nut, or oat milk<br />1 tbs. arrowroot or kudzu<br />1 tbs. agar flakes<br />1/2 cup raw pignola nuts<br />1/2 cup silken tofu, drained<br />1/2 cup grape seed or canola oil<br />1/4 cup vegetable glycerin<br />1/4 cup lecithin granules<br />2 tsp. vanilla extract<br />2 tsp. clear liquid stevia<br />1/2 tsp. salt<br />1/4 tsp. orange extract<br />30 day lily flowers	<br /><br />1. Simmer the arrowroot and agar in the soy milk 5 minutes, stirring often, and taking care that it doesn\'t boil over.<br /><br />2. Purée with the remaining ingredients in a blender.<br /><br />2. Freeze in an ice cream machine according to the manufacturer’s directions.	<br /><br />Makes 5-1/2 cups<br /><br />Preparation time: 15 minutes<br /><br />Freezing tine: 2 hours','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(67,80,'Daylily Shoot and Tubers','The shoot\'s leaves spread out mostly along a plane, and light brown rhizomes spread out from a whitish base, each ending in a tuber with roots. This is the size of the best shoots.','','',NULL,NULL,82,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(68,81,'Daylily Flowers and Flower Buds','The stalked, funnel-shaped, 6-parted orange flower, with 1 pistil and 6 stamens, and a pale yellow line running the length of the petals and sepals, make these flowers distinct. The floppy, linear basal leaves are also characteristic of the plant.<br /><br />The open flowers, unopened orange flower buds, and wilted flowers on the short branches at the top of the leafless flower stalk are all good to eat.','','',NULL,NULL,83,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(69,82,'Daylily Tubers','Each slender rhizome coming from the base of the plant ends in a small, potato-like tuber that bears roots. Small, firm tubers are edible, albeit labor-intensive to prepare.','','',NULL,NULL,84,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(70,83,'Daylily Shoots','These light green shoots with linear, smooth-edged, pointed leaves can cover openings in the forest.','','',NULL,NULL,85,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(71,84,'Daylily Flowers','These showy, orange, short-stalked, funnel-shaped flowers consist of 3 similar petals and sepals, each with a yellow line running down its length; 6 pollen-covered stamens, and 1 pistil. ','','',NULL,NULL,86,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(72,85,'Daylily Flower Buds','This bud\'s for you!<br /><br />Delicious cooked in soups, stews, or casseroles, you can use these cylindrical, orange-yellow flower buds, which grow on short, branched stems at the top of the leafless flower stalk, in recipes that call for string beans.','','',NULL,NULL,87,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(73,86,'Iris Shoot','This poisonous shoot resembles a young daylily shoot, but the leaves are angled upward more acutely, and the green base is green, not white. Most importantly, there\'s one stout rhizome underground rather than radiating slender rhizomes, and no tubers.','','',NULL,NULL,88,0,'1','',0,NULL),(74,87,'Daffodil Shoots','Poisonous daffodil shoots\' leaves point almost straight up, not partially outward, there\'s no white base, and no tubers underground.','','',NULL,NULL,89,0,'1','',0,NULL),(75,89,'Black Bean Soup with Epazote','Black Bean Soup with Epazote<br /><br />Epazote, plus other traditional Mexican seasonings, creates a wonderful soup that far surpasses what you’d get in a Mexican restaurant.	Miso, used in traditional Japanese cuisine, makes it especially creamy, and adds the necessary salt.<br /><br />1/4 cup olive oil<br />2 yellow onions, chopped<br />4 cloves of garlic, chopped<br />1/2 cup mellow miso<br />1-1/2 cup cooked black beans<br />2 cups vegetable stock<br />1/2 cup cilantro<br />The juice of 1/2 lime<br />1 tsp. Tabasco sauce<br />1 tsp. cumin, ground<br />1 tsp. oregano, ground<br />1/2 tsp. black peppercorns, ground into 1 tsp.<br />1/2 tbs. fresh epazote, finely chopped, or tsp. dried epazote, ground	<br /><br />1. Sauté the onions in the olive oil 15 minutes or until lightly browned.<br /><br />2. Add the garlic and sauté another 5 minutes.<br /><br />3. Purée with 1 cups of the beans and the remaining ingredients in a blender, in 2 batches.<br /><br />4. Bring to a boil with the remaining beans over medium heat, stirring constantly, reduce the heat to low, cover, and simmer 5 minutes.	<br /><br />Serves 4<br /><br />Preparation time: 40 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(76,90,'Young Epazote','The alternate, lance-shaped to oblong leaves and branches should lead you to smell this plant to confirm its identity.','','',NULL,NULL,90,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(77,91,'Epazote in Flower','This resinous-smelling, branching plant has lance-shaped to oblong, alternate, wavy-toothed leaves. While all field guides call the tiny flowers, which grow on spikes arising from the leaf axils,  green, you can see that they have 5 *white* petals. Masses of tiny, green flower buds and similar-looking green fruits normally makes them hard to see, but spotted them after only 28 years!','','',NULL,NULL,91,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(78,92,'Lamb\'s-quarters','Lamb\'s-quarters, an edible plant that people have confused with epazote, has diamond-shaped toothed leaves, a whitish powder on the leaves\' undersides, and virtually no odor.','','',NULL,NULL,92,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(79,93,'Wild Guacamole','Wild Guacamole<br /><br />Epazote, the classic herb of Mexican cuisine, finds its natural home in this south-of-the-border spread.<br /><br />2 ripe avocados<br />The juice of half a lemon<br />2 cloves of garlic, chopped<br />1/2 tbs. fresh epazote, finely chopped<br />1 tsp. Vege-sal<br />1 tsp. hot pepper sauce or Tabasco sauce<br />1/2 tsp. cumin, ground<br />1/2 tsp. black pepper, ground	<br /><br />Mash the avocado with the other ingredients.	<br /><br />Makes 2 cups<br /><br />Preparation time: 10 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(80,95,'Daylily Tubers','The underground parts distinguish the daylily from poisonous look-alikes: Slender rhizomes spread from the white base. Each rhizome ends in an oblong tuber, from which roots grow.','','',NULL,NULL,93,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(81,96,'Field Pennycress in Flower','The lance-shaped, alternate leaves clasping the stem, and tiny flowers on racemes toward the top of the plant, characterize it before the seeds appear.','','',NULL,NULL,94,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(82,97,'Field Pennycress Flowers','The short-stalked, small, 5-petaled flowers clustered above the flat, notched fruits make identification of this plant certain.','','',NULL,NULL,95,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(83,98,'Field Pennycress Seeds','These flat, circular, notched seeds account for the plant\'s name, and make it stand out from all its relatives.','','',NULL,NULL,96,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(84,99,'A Stand of Field Pennycress','Field pennycress stands such as this one often spread across sunny, disturbed sites, making it easy to harvest in quantity.','','',NULL,NULL,97,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(85,100,'Field Peppergrass','Similar to field pennycress and also edible, field peppergrass\'s *(L. campestre)* flat, circular seed pods aren\'t notched.','','',NULL,NULL,98,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(86,101,'Poor Man\'s Pepper','Poor man\'s pepper *(Lepidium virginicum)* is a good edible related to field pennycress, but with smaller seedpods that aren\'t notched.','','',NULL,NULL,99,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(87,102,'Thai Peanut Sauce with Field Pennycress','This basic sauce turns virtually any combination of stir-fried ingredients into an authentic-tasting Thai dish, and the field pennycress provides the fire.	<br /><br />1/2 cup field pennycress seeds or leaves, or to taste<br />1/2 cup peanut butter<br />2 cups coconut milk<br />1 pear<br />The juice of 1 lime<br />2 tbs. peanut oil<br />2 cloves of garlic<br />2 tbs. cilantro<br />1/2 tsp. black pepper<br />1 small onion<br />2 tbs. brown rice vinegar<br />3 tbs. tamari soy sauce<br />1 tsp. dark sesame oil	<br /><br />1. Purée all ingredients in a blender.<br /><br />2. Transfer to a saucepan, bring to a boil over medium heat, stirring constantly, reduce the heat to low and simmer, uncovered, 5 minutes, stirring often.<br /><br />Makes 4 cups<br /><br />15 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(88,104,'Yellow Foxtail Grass','The black seeds visible in the straight, cylindrical seed heads look like they\'ll start falling out with just a little rubbing.','','',NULL,NULL,100,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(89,105,'Green Foxtail Grass','The weight of the ripe seeds looks like it\'s making this species bend over, but that\'s the way it grows.','','',NULL,NULL,101,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(90,106,'Yellow Foxtail Grass Seed Head','The cylindrical seed head of this species stands erect no matter how ripe the seeds get.','','',NULL,NULL,102,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(91,107,'Heavenly Risotto','Heavenly Risotto	<br /><br />Here’s a quick, wonderful grain recipe you can make in short order with a pressure cooker. The crunchy foxtail grass seeds add some crunchiness in an otherwise soft dish, and, along with the black walnuts, make it even more special.	<br /><br />4-1/4 cups water or vegetable stock<br />2 cups long-grain brown rice<br />1/4 cup foxtail grass seeds<br />1 red onion, chopped<br />1/2 cup mellow miso<br />2 celery stalks, sliced<br />4 cloves of garlic, chopped<br />2 tbs. olive oil<br />2 tbs. All-purpose Seasoning (available in health food stores)<br />1 14-oz. package of dairy-free soy mozzarella cheese, grated<br />1/2 cup roasted black walnuts or commercial walnuts, chopped	<br /><br />1. Bring all ingredients except the nuts to pressure in a pressure cooker and pressure cook on the highest setting 20 minutes on a simmer plate, then allow to reach room temperature naturally (or simmer, covered, in a saucepan, 45 to 50 minutes, or until all the liquid is absorbed.)<br /><br />2. Serve topped with the nuts.	<br /><br />Serves 6 to 8<br /><br />Preparation time: 15<br /><br />Cooking time: 25 or 50 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(92,109,'Simple Garlic Mustard Pesto','Simple Garlic Mustard Pesto	<br /><br />Garlic mustard makes of such excellent pesto, that it works superbly with the most simple pesto ingredients. Use it with pasta, or as a savory spread on bread or crackers.<br /><br />2 cups garlic mustard leaves, flowers and top stems<br />1/4 cup commercial garlic cloves<br />1-1/2 cups olive oil<br />1 cup goutweed or parsley<br />1 cup fresh basil<br />2 cups black walnuts, commercial walnuts, or pignola nuts<br />1/4 cup brewer’s yeast<br />1 tsp. salt	<br /><br />1. Chop the garlic and goutweed or parsley in a food processor.<br /><br />2. Add the remaining ingredients and process into a slightly chunky paste.	<br /><br />Makes 3 cups<br /><br />Preparation time: 5 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(93,110,'Garlic Mustard Sprouts','The small, strap-shaped, smooth-edged leaf of each reddish sprout hangs from the top like a sideways flag.','','',NULL,NULL,103,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(94,111,'Garlic Mustard Basal Rosette','The heavily veined, coarse-toothed, long-stalked, kidney-shaped basal leaves emerge from the central taproot.','','',NULL,NULL,104,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(95,112,'Garlic Mustard Basal Rosette and Taproot','The long, white, slender taproot is the source of the long-stalked, deeply veined, coarse-toothed, kidney-shaped basal leaves of varying sizes.','','',NULL,NULL,105,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(96,113,'Garlic Mustard Flower Stalk','The alternate leaves on the flower stalk resemble the basal leaves, but the leaf stalks are shorter, and the higher leaves are more triangular than kidney-shaped.','','',NULL,NULL,106,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(97,114,'Garlic Mustard Flower Bud','The flower bud, set near the heavily veined alternate leaves, looks like a smaller version of its relative, broccoli.','','',NULL,NULL,107,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(98,115,'Garlic Mustard Flowers','Garlic mustard\'s small, white flowers, growing clustered together, all have 4 petals configured like a cross, typical of the mustard family.','','',NULL,NULL,108,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(99,116,'Garlic Mustard Seed Pods','Garlic mustard\'s oblong, dark brown seeds grow in rows in the long, narrow pods, maturing as the rest of the plant dies.','','',NULL,NULL,109,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(100,117,'Garlic Mustard Seeds','These long, narrow, dark brown seeds are very easy to collect, and great to use.','','',NULL,NULL,110,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(101,118,'White Violet in Flower','Various species of violets have less deeply veined leaves with smaller teeth than garlic mustard, and no odor. ','','',NULL,NULL,111,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(102,120,'Knot Pudding','Knot Pudding	<br /><br />This pudding came out so well, I entered it into my computer while I was still eating it. Tasty and simple, the ingredients balance each other perfectly. The knotweed is sour, the raisins and stevia are sweet, the tapioca makes it creamy, and the other flavorings fit in just right. Serve it hot or cold.	<br /><br />8 cups soy milk, nut milk, or oat milk<br />2 cup Japanese knotweed shoots, sliced<br />1 cup raisins<br />1 cup tapioca pearls<br />2 tsp. liquid stevia<br />2 tsp. vanilla extract<br />1/2 tsp. orange extract<br />1/4 tsp. nutmeg, ground<br />1/4 tsp. salt<br />1 cup raspberries or other berries	<br /><br />1. Bring all ingredients except the raspberries to a boil in a heavy saucepan over medium heat, stirring constantly.<br /><br />2. Reduce the heat to low and simmer, uncovered, 30 minutes, stirring often.<br /><br />3. Serve topped with the berries.	<br /><br />Serves 6 to 8<br /><br />Preparation time: 10 minutes<br /><br />Cooking time: 30 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(103,121,'Japanese Knotweed Shoots','Both the smaller, younger shoot, and the older one, have nodes and joints, and are dappled with red, but the older one has bulging-triangular to arrow-shaped, smooth-edged, alternate leaves too.','','',NULL,NULL,112,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(104,122,'Japanese Knotweed Leaf, Flowers, and Skeleton','The spike of small white flowers emerges from the axil of the smooth-edged, 3-sided, bulging, pointed leaf. The spikes persist, along with the zigzag of dead, jointed stems, through the winter and into the following spring.','','',NULL,NULL,113,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(105,123,'A Stand of Japanese Knotweed Shoots','These green, jointed shoots, flecked with red, magenta, and pink, come up in dense stands among the bamboo-like remnants of the previous year\'s plants. Whitish sheaths grow above each of the joints, and the developing leaves\' margins are still inrolled.','','',NULL,NULL,114,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(106,124,'Japanese Knotweed in Flower','The spikes of tiny white flowers emerge from the leaf axils, which also give rise to the smooth-edged, pointed, alternate leaves that are shaped like bulging triangles. ','','',NULL,NULL,115,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(107,125,'Giant Knotweed Shoot','Giant knotweed *(P. sachalinense),* less common than Japanese knotweed, is very similar, only larger. You can use both plants the same way.','','',NULL,NULL,116,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(108,127,'Chonce (From *The Wild Vegan Cookbook* by \"Wildman\" Steve Brill)','This unusual hot seasoning includes ingredients associated with Indian, Mediterranean, and health food cuisines. Even plain tasting leaves like lady\'s thumb won\'t be bland when you season them with chonce. Add it to soups, grains, spreads, or sauces to enhance their flavor. Take a chonce and try it!	<br /><br />3 tbs. peanut oil<br />3 tbs. corn oil or flaxseed oil<br />2 tsp. whole cumin seeds<br />1/4 tsp. crushed red pepper<br />1/4 cup fresh basil, chopped; or 4 tsp. dried basil, ground<br />1 tbs. garlic, chopped<br />1/2 tsp. coriander, ground<br />6 tbs. brewer’s yeast<br />1/4 tsp. cloves, ground<br />1 tsp. tamari soy sauce	<br /><br />1. Cook the cumin seeds and crushed red pepper in the peanut oil and corn oil over low heat 2 to 3 minutes, stirring constantly.<br /><br />2. Add the basil and garlic, and cook another minute, stirring often.<br /><br />3. Add the remaining ingredients, remove the pan from the heat, and allow everything to cook in the hot pan another 2 minutes, stirring often.<br /><br />Makes 1/2 cup<br /><br />Preparation and cooking time: 10 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(109,128,'Chauncey\'s Squash Soup','Chauncey’s Squash Soup	<br /><br />Using my Chonce recipe as a seasoning, this 5-ingredient recipe gets a 10!	<br /><br />3 cups vegetable stock<br />2 cups cooked squash<br />2 cups lady\'s thumb leaves<br />1/4 cup mellow miso<br />1/4 cup Chonce	<br /><br />1. Bring all ingredients to a boil in a saucepan, reduce the heat to low, and simmer 5 minutes.<br /><br />2. Purée in a blender, beginning at low speed, and hold down the blender cover with a towel at first, to prevent eruption.	<br /><br />Serves 4<br /><br />Preparation/cooking time: 10 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(110,129,'Lady\'s Thumb in Flower','The slender racemes of tiny pink flowers grow at the tips of the branches, while the smooth-edged, alternate, lance-shaped, short-stalked leaves grow from the stems sheathed, hair-fringed nodes.','','',NULL,NULL,117,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(111,130,'Immature Lady\'s Thumb','Faint, dark chevrons mark the center of the short-stalked, lance-shaped, alternate leaves.','','',NULL,NULL,118,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(112,131,'Lady\'s Thumb—side view','The raceme of tiny, pink flowers at the top of the jointed stalk is typical of this plant. So are the fringes of short hairs above the sheathes on the stem, and the short-stalked, alternate, lance-shaped, smooth-edged leaves. ','','',NULL,NULL,119,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(113,132,'Lady\'s Thumb Stand','Lady\'s thumb usually grows in dense stands like these, displaying many upright racemes of tiny, pink fl0wers above the leaves, to attract pollinating insects.','','',NULL,NULL,120,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(114,133,'Lady\'s Thumb Flowers','The striking pink color of these small flowers, arranged cylindrically on a raceme, make a stand of these plants noticeable.','','',NULL,NULL,121,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(115,134,'Lady\'s Thumb\'s Fringed Sheath','The sheathes wrapped around the stems\' nodes are fringed with very short hairs, distinguishing lady\'s thumb from it\'s less-than-tasty relatives.','','',NULL,NULL,122,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(116,135,'Pennsylvania Smartweed','Pennsylvania smartweed *(P. pensylvanicum)* looks like lady\'s thumb, but it\'s bigger, and its nodes lack lady\'s thumb\'s fringe of hair. Too acrid to eat, there\'s only 1 good thing to do with Pennsylvania smartweed—send it back to Pennsylvania!','','',NULL,NULL,123,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(117,137,'test','','','',NULL,NULL,124,0,NULL,'',0,'D'),(118,138,'Creamed Lamb\'s-quarters','Creamed Lamb’s-Quarters	<br /><br />Here’s a variation of a classic American spinach recipe made using lamb’s-quarters, and further transformed by vegan ingredients replacing the cream.	<br /><br />2 cups lamb’s-quarters or spinach, chopped<br />2 tbs. silken tofu<br />2 tbs. water<br />2 tbs. corn or flaxseed oil<br />1 tbs. lecithin granules<br />1/8 tsp. liquid stevia<br />4 cloves of garlic, peeled<br />1/2 tsp. salt<br />1/4 tsp. black pepper, ground<br />1/8 tsp. nutmeg	<br /><br />1. Purée the water, tofu, corn oil, lecithin, and stevia in a blender.<br /><br />2. Combine with the remaining ingredients in a saucepan, cover, and cook over low heat until just wilted.<br /><br />3. Remove and discard the garlic.	<br /><br />Serves 4 to 6<br /><br />Preparation/cooking time: 20 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(119,139,'Lamb\'s-quarters in Flower','The branching stalk, diamond-shaped, wavy toothed leaves, leaf stalks half the length of the leaves, and spikes of tiny flowers flowers coming from the leaf stalks, help you zero in on this common edible plant.','','',NULL,NULL,125,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(120,140,'Lamb\'s-quarters Leaves from Below','The diamond-shaped, wavy toothed leaves, with leaf stalks half the length of the leaves, are distinctly mealy white underneath.','','',NULL,NULL,126,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(121,141,'Large Lamb\'s-quarters','The reddish stem with lots of branches, and the diamond-shaped leaves twice as long as the leaf stalks, plus the leaves\' whitish undersides, show what you need to know to recognize this plant.','','',NULL,NULL,127,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(122,142,'Lamb\'s-quarters Flowers','Many dense spikes of tiny, green, spherical flowers arise from the leaf axils.','','',NULL,NULL,128,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(123,143,'Young Lamb\'s-quarters Leaves','The youngest leaves are whitish all over. When they get a little larger, they\'re linear, not diamond-shaped.','','',NULL,NULL,129,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(124,144,'Lamb\'s-quarters Stand','This plant often grows dense stands that make harvesting easy. And the branches are loaded with wavy toothed, diamond-shaped (linear when young) leaves, whitish underneath, making this plant easy to spot.','','',NULL,NULL,130,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(125,145,'Orache','This bitter-tasting plant looks a little lamb\'s-quarters, but its leaves are arrow-shaped, not diamond-shaped.','','',NULL,NULL,149,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(126,146,'Epazote','Epazote, which you use as a seasoning, has narrow leaves that are neither diamond-shaped nor whitish underneath. ','','',NULL,NULL,131,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(127,148,'Mature Mugwort Leaf','Mugwort\'s toothed leaves are deeply divided into many lobes, and fine, matted hairs give their undersides a whitish appearance.','','',NULL,NULL,132,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(128,149,'Mugwort in Flower','The lower leaves, whitish underneath, are very deeply cut, while the younger upper leaves are less lobed or linear. Tiny, greenish flowers emerge from the branches near the plant\'s top.','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(129,150,'Mugwort Flowers','The young, upper leaves, still whitish underneath, are less lobed or linear than the lower ones. And the tiny, reddish-brown tipped, greenish, wind-pollinated flowers grow in quantity on panicles arising from the leaf axils.','','',NULL,NULL,133,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(130,151,'Mugwort Leaf Underside','The deeply lobed leaves look whitish underneath due to mats of tiny hairs.','','',NULL,NULL,134,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(131,152,'Mugwort Stand','Mugwort grows in dense stands, taking over habitats. The tall plant\'s deeply lobed leaves, whitish underneath, and the many, tiny, green flowers make it easy to spot.','','',NULL,NULL,135,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(132,154,'Pineapple Weed in Flower','This small plant has finely divided, feathery, branched, alternate leaves, and small, stalked, flattened cone-shaped flowers set inside a cup of interlocking bracts.','','',NULL,NULL,136,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(133,155,'Pineapple Weed Young Leaves','These leaves look feathery because they branch 3 times, and the leaflets become progressively more narrow.','','',NULL,NULL,137,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(134,156,'Pineapple Weed Flowers','These small, rounded, stalked, cone-shaped, yellow-green flower heads, set in a greenish cup of interlocking bracts, consist of many tiny but distinct flowers bunched together. Along with the pineapple scent (not shown), and the finely divided leaves, they make this small plant easy to recognize.','','',NULL,NULL,138,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(135,157,'Chamomile','This closely related but larger plant, which you use the same way as pineapple weed, has white ray flowers, which pineapple weed lacks. And its larger disk is yellow, not yellow-green.','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(136,159,'Garlic Mustard Seed Pods','After garlic mustard dies in its second year, the whitish skeleton bears long, narrow, alternate seed pods with rows of tiny, elongated, black seeds.','','',NULL,NULL,139,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(137,160,'Creamed Pokeweed','Smothered in a special vegan cream sauce, pokeweed simply can’t be beat.<br /><br />9 cups young pokeweed shoots, chopped<br />1 14-oz. can of coconut milk<br />1/4 cup sesame oil<br />1/2 tsp. cloves, ground<br />1/4 cup arrowroot or kudzu<br />1/4 cup mellow miso (available in health food stores)<br />1-1/2 tbs. fresh basil<br />2 tsp. turmeric<br />1 tsp. powdered commercial or ground wild ginger, or 1 tbs. fresh commercial or wild ginger<br />4 common spicebush berries, or 1 tsp. allspice, ground<br />1 tsp. coriander, ground<br />1/8 tsp. Cayenne hot pepper, or to taste<br /><br />1. Boil the pokeweed in 2 changes of rapidly boiling water, 1 minute, 1 minute, and 15 minutes, as directed above.<br /><br />2. Meanwhile, purée the remaining ingredients in a blender.<br /><br />3. Bring this sauce to a boil in a saucepan over medium heat, stirring constantly.<br /><br />4. Reduce the heat to low and simmer the sauce, covered, 5 minutes, stirring occasionally.<br /><br />5. Drain the properly cooked pokeweed thoroughly, stir it into to the sauce, and simmer 3 minutes over low heat, stirring occasionally.	<br /><br />Serves 6<br /><br />Preparation/cooking time: 40 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(138,161,'Pokeweed Taproot, Shoot, Flowers, and Berries','Pokeweed\'s upward-pointing, large, elliptical, entire, alternate leaves surround a stout, unbranched, purple-tinged stalk in early spring.<br /><br />The small, stalked, white, 5-sepaled flower, with a green, button-like, central ovary, grows on a drooping raceme from summer to fall, accompanied by the same leaves as the shoot.<br /><br />The indented, shiny, dark purple berries grow on drooping, magenta racemes in the summer and fall.<br /><br />The large, light tan taproot is perennial.','','',NULL,NULL,140,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(139,162,'Pokeweed Shoot','Entire, alternate, elliptical, stalked leaves on a stout, purple-tinged stem 6 t0 8 inches tall characterize pokeweed shoots when they\'re suitable for cooking.','','',NULL,NULL,141,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(140,163,'Pokeweed Shoot and Taproot','Prepared properly, this shoot, with its entire, elliptical, alternate, stalked leaves, is delicious, while the light tan taproot is deadly!','','',NULL,NULL,142,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(141,164,'Pokeweed Flowers','Growing along a raceme, the stalked flowers have 5 petal-like sepals and a green, button-like, segmented ovary.','','',NULL,NULL,143,0,'1','',0,NULL),(142,165,'Mature Pokeweed','When this large, branching plant, with its entire, elliptical, alternate leaves, and drooping racemes of white, 5-parted flowers, reaches this stage, it becomes very poisonous.','','',NULL,NULL,144,0,'1','',0,NULL),(143,166,'Poke Berries','Dark purple when mature, these shiny, indented, segmented berries, growing on magenta racemes, are too dangerous to eat. Although some people allegedly survived downing them, the seeds inside are very poisonous. ','','',NULL,NULL,145,0,'1','',0,NULL),(144,168,'Poor Man\'s Pepper Sauté','Poor man’s pepper and spices make plain ol’ tofu anything but bland. Serve with whole grains or bread.	<br /><br />3 tbs. olive oil<br />2 14-oz. packages of soft tofu, drained and diced<br />1/3 cup poor man’s pepper leaves, chopped<br />2 tbs. Old Bay Seasoning<br />2 tbs. lemon juice<br />1/2 tsp. Vege-sal	(available in health food stores) or seasoned salt<br /><br />Sauté all ingredients in the olive oil for 10 minutes.	<br /><br />Serves 4 to 6<br /><br />Preparation/Cooking time: 15 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(145,169,'Poor Man\'s Pepper in Flower','The linear to lance-shaped leaves with teeth pointing toward the leaf tips, and the tiny, white flowers on terminal racemes above nearly circular, flat seeds, make this branching plant easy to recognize.','','',NULL,NULL,146,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(146,170,'Poor Man\'s Pepper Basal Rosette','The lobes on this early spring rosette point toward the leaf tips. Along with a lack of hairs or milky sap, that makes it easy to distinguish from similar plants.','','',NULL,NULL,147,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(147,171,'Poor Man\'s Pepper Maturing Rosette','As the rosette begins to produce a flower stalk, the lobes transform into sharp teeth which point toward the leaf\'s tip.','','',NULL,NULL,148,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(148,172,'Mature Poor Man\'s Pepper','The branching, wiry plant, with stalkless, linear, alternate leaves and a raceme of flat, nearly circular seed pods with small, white flowers on top, creates the impression of a bottle brush. The characteristic teeth on the leaves pointing toward the leaf tip, and the slight notch at the tip of each seed pods, clinches the plant\'s identity.','','',NULL,NULL,150,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(149,173,'Field Peppergrass','Field Peppergrass *(Thlaspi arvense)*, also edible, is similar to poor man\'s pepper, but it\'s fuzzy, the seed pods are larger and longer, and the seed pod stalks are longer.','','',NULL,NULL,151,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(150,174,'Field Pennycress in Flower','Field pennycress *(Thlaspi arvense)*, also edible, looks like poor man\'s pepper, but the larger seeds are deeply notched, and the base of the leaves clasp the stem.','','',NULL,NULL,152,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(151,175,'Shepherd\'s Purse in Flower','Shepherd\'s purse *(Capsella bursa-pastoris),* also resembles poor man\'s pepper, but the basal leaves\' blunt lobes point outward, the upper leaves clasp the stem, and the seed pods are heart-shaped.','','',NULL,NULL,153,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(152,177,'Purslane with Beets','Purslane with Beets	<br /><br />Here’s a match made in heaven. As you can tell after your first bite, this Turkish-style casserole can\'t be beet!	<br /><br />2-1/2 cups purslane, chopped<br />2 cups water<br />6 beets, sliced<br />1 small red onions, chopped<br />3 small tomatoes, chopped<br />3 cup beet greens, chopped<br />1/2 cup basmati brown rice<br />1/2 cup fresh parsley, chopped<br />2 tbs. dill weed, chopped<br />3 tbs. olive oil<br />1 tbs. lemon juice<br />2 tsp. Vege-sal (available in health food stores) or seasoned salt	<br /><br />1. Place the rice in an oiled casserole dish.<br /><br />2. Mix together all the other ingredients and place on top of the rice.<br /><br />3. Bake in a preheated 350 degree oven, covered, 90 minutes, or until the rice is tender.	<br /><br />Serves 6 to 8	Excellent<br /><br />Preparation time: 10 min.<br /><br />Cooking time: 90 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(153,178,'Young Purslane','The thick, smooth, succulent, sprawling, purple-red stem, and the stalkless, fleshy, paddle-shaped leaves, are all you need to see to recognize this distinctive plant.','','',NULL,NULL,154,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(154,179,'Purslane Flower','You hardly ever see purslane\'s tiny, yellow flower, which only opens during sunny summer mornings.','','',NULL,NULL,155,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(155,180,'Purslane Fruit and Seeds','The light green, ovoid fruit capsules split along the middle to release the tiny, rounded, black seeds.','','',NULL,NULL,156,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(156,181,'Spotted Spurge','This creeping plant, spotted spurge, *(Euphorbia supina),* with its wiry stem, elliptical, spotted leaves, white flowers, and sickly white sap, often grows right along with purslane, which it doesn\'t really resemble. Don\'t carelessly bag this toxic species along with your dinner!','','',NULL,NULL,157,0,'1','',0,NULL),(157,183,'Red Clover in Flower','The magenta flower head of red clover, composed of many tiny, tubular flowers bunched together, grows atop a long, slender, downy, branching flower stalk. The palmate-compound leaves consist of 3 oval to elliptical leaflets divided in half by a midrib that runs down their lengths. Each leaflet is marked by a *V*-shaped chevron.','','',NULL,NULL,158,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(158,184,'Red Clover Flower','The rounded flower head is composed of many tiny, narrow, 2-sided magenta flowers. It grows above a slender, downy flower stalk that bears alternate, compound leaves consisting of 3 oval to elliptical leaflets, each marked with a *V*-shaped chevron. ','','',NULL,NULL,159,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(159,185,'Yellow Wood Sorrel in Flower','Yellow wood sorrel *(Oxalis stricta)* and its relatives have a compound leaf consisting of 3 leaflets, like clovers, but they\'re heart-shaped, and the 5-parted, radially symmetrical yellow flower is completely different from red clover\'s flower head.','','',NULL,NULL,160,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(160,187,'Peachy Keen Ice Cream with Red Clover Sprinkles','Here’s a flavorful, creamy ice cream you can make with wild or commercial peaches, where my method of making vegan ice creams reaches perfection. And the red clover sprinkles give it a special touch.<br /><br />3 peaches, chopped<br />2-3/4 cups soy-rice milk, oat milk, or nut milk<br />1 tbs. arrowroot or kudzu<br />1 tbs. agar<br />1/2 raw cup pignola or cashew nuts<br />1/2 cup silken tofu, drained<br />1/4 cup lecithin granules (available in health food stores)<br />1/4 cup grape seed oil or canola oil<br />1/4 cup vegetable glycerin	 (available in health food stores)<br />1/4 cup flowers pulled off the flower heads of fresh red clovers<br /><br />1. Simmer the peaches in the soy-rice milk with the arrowroot and agar<br /><br />5 minutes or until the peaches are tender, stirring often.<br /><br />2. Freeze in an ice cream machine according to the manufacturer’s directions. 	<br /><br />3. Serve sprinkled with the red clover flowers<br /><br />Makes 5-1/2 cups<br /><br />Preparation time: 20<br /><br />Freezing time: 120 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(161,188,'rwar','','','',NULL,NULL,161,0,NULL,'',0,'D'),(162,189,'White Clover Flower','Tiny, long, 2-sided flowers crowd together to make this rounded flower head growing on top of a slender, leafless stalk.','','',NULL,NULL,162,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(163,190,'White Clover Leaf','The 3-parted palmate-compound leaf consists of 3 oval to elliptical leaflets, each with a seam running its length, a \"V\"-shaped chevron, and a tiny notch at the tip.','','',NULL,NULL,163,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(164,191,'Miso Soup with White Clover','Miso Nori Soup	<br /><br />Nori is  a seaweed that’s formed into a papery sheet, familiar to anyone who’s eaten sushi. Here it replaces the traditional wakame seaweed in traditional Japanese miso soup, and does a great job. My Vegan Fish Stock (yes, some fish really are vegans, especially the ones that read my Wild Vegan Cookbook) works perfectly here too. And white clover flowers add a perfectly wild touch!<br /><br />8 cups Vegan Fish Stock<br />1-1/3 cup soft tofu, finely chopped<br />1-1/3 cup Nori Krinkles (instant nori, (available in health food stores)1/4 cup white clover flowers, pulled from fresh flower heads<br /><br />2/3 cup mellow miso	<br /><br />1. Simmer the tofu, nori flakes, and white clover flowers in the fish stock 10 minutes.<br /><br />2. Lower a strainer into the soup and incorporate the miso by stirring it into the soup with a wooden spoon, or purée it with some of the stock in a blender.	<br /><br />Serves 6<br /><br />Preparation/cooking time: 20 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(165,192,'Vegan Fish Stock','Vegan Fish Stock	<br /><br />How do you make fish stock, the base of so many soups and sauces, without fish? Either go fishing, or use a fish-flavored vegetarian ingredient, i.e., rockweed, the most common seaweed, along with the usual constituents of fish stock.	Use it in soups, sauces, or other recipes that call for stock.<br /><br />19 cups water<br />1 cup white wine<br />4 large onions, coarsely chopped<br />4 large carrots including the tops, coarsely-chopped<br />The juice of 1 lemon + the rind, coarsely-chopped<br />1/2 cup parsley<br />2 tbs. bayberry leaves *(Myrica spp.)* or bay leaves<br />2 cups rockweed *(Fucus vesiculosus)* or other seaweed, wild  or commercial (available in health food stores or East Asian grocery stores)<br />1 tbs. thyme<br />1 tsp. white pepper, ground	<br /><br />1. Simmer all ingredients in a large saucepan, covered, 30 minutes.<br /><br />2. Strain. out the solid ingredients.	<br /><br />Makes 20 cups<br /><br />Cooking time: 45 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(166,194,'Yellow Wood Sorrel in Flower','Yellow wood sorrel *(Oxalis stricta)* and its relatives have a compound leaf consisting of 3 leaflets, like clovers, but they\'re heart-shaped, the 5-parted, radially symmetrical yellow flower is completely different from white clover\'s flower head, and the fruit looks like a banana or pickle.','','',NULL,NULL,164,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(167,195,'Sheel Sorrel Basal Leaves and Stem','The arrow-shaped, long-stalked basal leaf resembles a sheep\'s face. The leaves on the stem are similar but smaller, with papery sheathes adjacent to the leaf axils. Branches include long clusters of tiny flowers.','','',NULL,NULL,165,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(168,196,'Sheep Sorrel Young Basal Leaves','The youngest of these long-stalked basal leaves are oval, whereas the older ones are arrow-shaped.','','',NULL,NULL,166,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(169,197,'Sheep Sorrel Flower Stalk','Tiny yellow-green male flowers and equally small reddish male flowers grow along the branching flower stalk.','','',NULL,NULL,167,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(170,198,'Schav','Since the leaf resembles a calf\'s face as much as a sheep\'s this traditional Jewish soup, usually made with dairy products, is called *shav,* which means *calf* in Yiddish. It\'s great served hot on a cold day or cold on a hot day, so try it—don\'t be sheepish!<br /><br />8 cups vegetable stock<br />6 cups sheep sorrel or garden sorrel<br />2 medium red onions, finely-chopped<br />1 tbs. flaxseeds, ground<br />1/2 tbs. Vege-sal (available in health food stores) or 3/4 tsp. salt, or to taste<br />1/4 tsp. black pepper, or to taste, ground<br />1 tbs. lemon juice<br />1 tbs. corn oil<br />1/2 tbs. lecithin granules<br />1 cup silken tofu, diced	<br /><br />1. Bring 3/4 of the stock, plus the sheep sorrel, onion, flaxseeds, Vege-sal, and black pepper to a boil in a saucepan over medium heat, reduce the heat to low, and simmer, covered, 5 minutes.<br /><br />2. Meanwhile, puree the lemon juice, corn oil, and lecithin granules in a blender with the remaining stock.<br /><br />3. Stir this the into the soup with the tofu, adjust the seasonings to taste, and add additional lemon juice if desired.<br /><br />4. Serve hot or chilled.<br /><br />Serves 6<br /><br />Cooking/preparation time: 30 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(171,200,'Field Bindweed','Field bindweed\'s *(Convolvulus arvensis) arrow-shaped leaves might make people confuse it with sheep sorrel, but field bindweed is a vine, not an upright plant, and it has a large, white, funnel-shaped flower, ompletely different from sheep sorrel\'s.','','',NULL,NULL,168,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(172,201,'Chicory Large Rosette','By the time chicory\'s basal leaves develop lobes, they\'re already very bitter-tasting.','','',NULL,NULL,170,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(173,202,'Mature Shepherd\'s Purse','The blunt-lobed basal leaves, and the long, slender flower stalks with small, alternate, stalkless leaves, tiny clusters of white flowers, and triangular to heart-shaped seed pods, make this common, edible \"weed\" easy to recognize.','','',NULL,NULL,171,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(174,203,'Shepherd\'s Purse Basal Rosette','It\'s time to collect shepherd\'s purse when you\'ve identified the basal rosette with its blunt-tipped lobes or teeth pointing outward, the largest lobe at the leaf\'s tip, and no colored sap (as is clearly not shown here).','','',NULL,NULL,172,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(175,204,'Shepherd\'s Purse Flowers and Seeds','Due to the long leaf stalk, shepherd\'s purse\'s 4-petaled, white flowers, and heart-shaped to triangular seed pods form much looser clusters than their short-stalked relatives.','','',NULL,NULL,173,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(176,205,'Shepherd\'s Purse in Flower','Fully grown shepherd\'s purse has lobed basal leaves under long, slender flower stalks festooned with loose clusters of heart-shaped to triangular seeds pods, and tighter clusters of tiny, 4-petaled white flowers at the summits.','','',NULL,NULL,174,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(177,206,'Common Dandelion Basal Rosette','The common dandelion\'s *(Taraxacum officinale)* edible basal leaves\' teeth point toward the leaf\'s base, not outward.','','',NULL,NULL,175,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(178,207,'Chicory Basal Rosette','Similar to shepherd\'s purse, chicory\'s edible basal leaves contain a white, milky sap, and there\'s usually some reddish discoloration, plus some hairs on the leaf midrib\'s underside.','','',NULL,NULL,176,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(181,211,'Curried Bok Choy with Shepherd\'s Purse','The Chinese bok choy does great in an Indian context, with shepherd\'s purse leaves adding a wild touch.	<br /><br />1/4 cup peanut oil<br />2 tbs. dark sesame oil<br />3 cups bok choy leaves, chopped<br />1 cup shepherd\'s purse leaves, chopped<br />1 14-oz package of soft tofu, drained and diced<br /><br />Sauce:<br /><br />1-1/2 cups water<br />2 tbs. peanut butter<br />2 tbs. curry powder, or to taste<br />2 tbs. soy mayonnaise<br />2 tsp. arrowroot or kudzu (available in health food stores)<br />1 tbs. lemon juice	<br /><br />1. Purée all sauce ingredients in a blender, or mix with a whisk.<br /><br />2. Mix the oils together.<br /><br />3. Successively stir-fry the bok choy with the shepherd\'s purse, then the tofu, in a wok or large frying pan, using half the oils at a time.<br /><br />4. Add the sauce, bring to a boil over medium heat, stirring constantly, reduce the heat to low, cover, and simmer 10 minutes, stirring occasionally.	<br /><br />Serves 6<br /><br />Prep/cooking time: 30 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(179,208,'Poor Man\'s Pepper Basal Rosette','Poor man\'s pepper\'s *(Lepidium virginicum)*  edible basal leaves have teeth pointing toward the leaf\'s tip, not outward like shepherd\'s purse.','','',NULL,NULL,177,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(180,209,'Wild Lettuce Basal Rosette','Wild lettuce *(Lactuca canadense)* has edible young basal leaves with shallow teeth, a midrib that\'s triangular in cross-section, and white milky sap, all different from shepherd\'s purse.','','',NULL,NULL,178,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(182,212,'Yellow Violet','Avoid all violet species with yellow flowers, such as this round-leaf yellow violet (*Viola rotundifolia)*, since they may cause nausea and vomiting.','','',NULL,NULL,179,0,'1','',0,NULL),(183,213,'Common Blue Violet in Flower','The heart-shaped, shallow-toothed leaves, along with the violet, 5-petaled flower growing on a long, leafless, slender flower stalk, plus the flower\'s deep veins and white beard, make this common species unmistakable.','','',NULL,NULL,180,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(184,214,'Scalloped Cauliflower with Violets','Here’s a simple, wonderful vegetable dish you can get into the oven in 10 minutes. Rich, tasty, nutritious, and filling, it’s ideal when you have a bagful of violets, but and not much time to cook.	<br /><br />1 cauliflower, broken into florets<br />2 cups vegan cheddar cheese, grated<br />2 cups violet leaves, chopped<br />1.5 cups dried whole-grain bread crumbs<br />2 tbs. olive oil<br />1 tsp. rosemary, ground<br />1 tsp. tarragon, ground<br />1 tsp. thyme, ground<br />2 cloves of garlic, crushed<br />1 tsp. Vege-sal (available in health food stores), or seasoned salt<br /><br />Stir all ingredients together, transfer to an oiled casserole dish and bake, uncovered, in a preheated 425 degree oven, 45 minutes, or until the cauliflower is tender and the cheese is melted.	<br /><br />Serves 4 to 6	Excellent<br /><br />Prep time: 10<br /><br />Baking time: 45 minutes','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(185,215,'Violet Seeds and Fruit Capsule','Packed in rows inside the ovate fruit, these white, spherical seeds taste delicious, but only if you\'re an ant!','','',NULL,NULL,181,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(186,216,'Violet Flower, Leaf, and Opened Fruit','The 5-parted, bilaterally symmetrical flower, with deeply veins on the lower petal and small spur behind, plus the long-stemmed, heart-shaped, shallow-toothed leaf, are easy to spot. You have to search along the ground for the 3-parted fruit, in late summer and autumn. ','','',NULL,NULL,182,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(187,217,'Violet Fruit','The opened, 3-parted fruit persists after the seeds have fallen out. If you look closely along the ground, you may even find it in the winter and locate your spring supply of violets in advance.','','',NULL,NULL,183,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(188,218,'White Violet','Now considered the same species as the common blue violet, this subspecies *(V. sororia albiflora)*, also edible, has white flowers substantially taller than the heart-shaped leaves. ','','',NULL,NULL,184,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(189,219,'Blue-and-White Violet','This common hybrid of the common blue violet *(V. sororia sororia)*and the white violet *(V. sororia albiflora)* is just as tasty as its parent subspecies.','','',NULL,NULL,185,0,NULL,'',0,NULL),(190,220,'Marsh Blue Violet','The swamp blue violet *(V. cucullata)* is one of very many edible violet species that populate the US. It grows in wetlands, and its blue flower is much taller than the heart-shaped leaves.','','',NULL,NULL,186,0,NULL,'',0,NULL);
/*!40000 ALTER TABLE `content_smalls` ENABLE KEYS */;
